Category.name: Category
Category.Definition: Definition of the category (group or type) of material, in more general terms than given by attribute Name.It is recommended to use common terms for the material category, the following list constitutes such a recommondation concrete, steel, aluminium, block, brick, stone, wood, glass, gypsum, plastic, earth. IFC4 CHANGE The attribute has been added at the end of attribute list.

Description.name: Description
Description.Definition: Definition of the material in more descriptive terms than given by attributes Name or Category.

IfcMaterialConstituent.Definition: Ifc Material Constituent is a single and identifiable part of an element which is constructed of a number of part (one or more) each having an individual material. The association of the material constituent to the part is provided by a keyword as value of the Name attribute. In order to identify and distinguish the part of the shape representation to which the material constituent applies the Ifc Product Definition Shape of the element has to include instances of Ifc Shape Aspect, using the same keyword for their Name attribute.
IfcMaterialConstituent.Name: Material Constituent

Category.name: Category
Category.Definition: Category of the material constituent, e.g. the role it has in the constituent set it belongs to.

Description.name: Description
Description.Definition: Definition of the material constituent in descriptive terms.

Fraction.name: Fraction
Fraction.Definition: Optional provision of a fraction of the total amount (volume or weight) that applies to the Ifc Material Constituent Set that is contributed by this Ifc Material Constituent.

Name.name: Name
Name.Definition: The name by which the material constituent is known.

IfcMaterialConstituentSet.Definition: Ifc Material Constituent Set is a collection of individual material constituents, each assigning a material to a part of an element. The parts are only identified by a keyword (as opposed to an Ifc Material Layer Set or Ifc Material Profile Set where each part has an individual shape parameter (layer thickness or layer profile).
IfcMaterialConstituentSet.Name: Material Constituent Set

Description.name: Description
Description.Definition: Definition of the material constituent set in descriptive terms.

Name.name: Name
Name.Definition: The name by which the constituent set is known.

IfcMaterialDefinition.Definition: Ifc Material Definition is a general supertype for all material related information items in IFC that have common material related properties that may include association of material with some shape parameters or assignments to identified parts of a component.There are three ways of assigning materials to a single component or multiple components they are characterized asby layer - assigning a material to a layer with constant thickness
IfcMaterialDefinition.Name: Material Definition

IfcMaterialLayer.Definition: Ifc Material Layer is a single and identifiable part of an element which is constructed of a number of layers (one or more). Each Ifc Material Layer has a constant thickness and is located relative to the referencing Ifc Material Layer Set along the material layer set base (Mls Base).Air gaps within a material layer set are represented as an Ifc Material Layer with the attribute Is Ventilated having the value TRUE or UNKNOWN. Such air gaps shall be interpreted as voids (not having a material).
IfcMaterialLayer.Name: Material Layer

Category.name: Category
Category.Definition: Category of the material layer, e.g. the role it has in the layer set it belongs to (such as load bearing, thermal insulation etc.). The list of keywords might be extended by model view definitions, however the following keywords shall apply in general

Description.name: Description
Description.Definition: Definition of the material layer in more descriptive terms than given by attributes Name or Category.

IsVentilated.name: Is Ventilated
IsVentilated.Definition: Indication of whether the material layer represents an air layer (or cavity).

LayerThickness.name: Layer Thickness
LayerThickness.Definition: The thickness of the material layer. The meaning of thickness depends on its usage. In case of building elements elements utilizing Ifc Material Layer Set Usage, the dimension is measured along the positive Layer Set Direction as specified in Ifc Material Layer Set Usage.

Name.name: Name
Name.Definition: The name by which the material layer is known.

Priority.name: Priority
Priority.Definition: The relative priority of the layer, expressed as normalised integer range 0..100. Controls how layers intersect in connections and corners of building elements a layer from one element protrudes into (i.e. displaces) a layer from another element in a joint of these elements if the former elements layer has higher priority than the latter. The priority value for a material layer in an element has to be set and maintained by software applications in relation to the material layers in connected elements.

IfcMaterialLayerSet.Definition: The Ifc Material Layer Set is a designation by which materials of an element constructed of a number of material layers is known and through which the relative positioning of individual layers can be expressed.The Material Layer Set Base (Mls Base) describes the imaginary axis along which the material layers are positioned.In case of assigning the Ifc Material Layer Set directly to an element or element type, the individual layers are stacked according to their position within the list of Material Layers without providing information on how to spatially relate the material layer information to the shape representation of the element or element type.
IfcMaterialLayerSet.Name: Material Layer Set

TotalThickness.name: Total Thickness
TotalThickness.Definition: Total thickness of the material layer set is derived from the function Ifc Mls Total Thickness.

Description.name: Description
Description.Definition: Definition of the Ifc Material Layer Set in descriptive terms.

LayerSetName.name: Layer Set Name
LayerSetName.Definition: The name by which the Ifc Material Layer Set is known.

IfcMaterialLayerWithOffsets.Definition: Ifc Material Layer With Offsets is a specialization of Ifc Material Layer enabling definition of offset values along edges (within the material layer set usage in parent layer set).It defines the assignment of two offset values for a material layer in its intended use within a material layer set. Offsets are applied to the edges of layered elements (that is, in directions perpendicular to the layer set direction). Offsets shall not be used in layer set direction, that is, for modelling gaps (or overlaps) between layers gaps shall be modeled as layers with appropriate material assignment for the void.
IfcMaterialLayerWithOffsets.Name: Material Layer With Offsets

OffsetDirection.Definition: Orientation of the offset shall be perpendicular to the parent layer set direction.

OffsetValues.name: Offset Values
OffsetValues.Definition: The numerical value of layer offset, in the direction of the axis assigned by the attribute Offset Direction. The Offset Values1 identifies the offset from the lower position along the axis direction (normally the start of the layer extrusion), the Offset Values2 identifies the offset from the upper position along the axis direction (normally the end of the layer extrusion).

IfcMaterialProfile.Definition: Ifc Material Profile is a single and identifiable cross section of an element which is constructed of a number of profiles (one or more).
IfcMaterialProfile.Name: Material Profile

Category.name: Category
Category.Definition: Category of the material profile, e.g. the role it has in the profile set it belongs to. The list of keywords might be extended by model view definitions, however the following keywords shall apply in general

Description.name: Description
Description.Definition: Definition of the material profile in descriptive terms.

Name.name: Name
Name.Definition: The name by which the material profile is known.

Priority.name: Priority
Priority.Definition: The relative priority of the profile, expressed as normalised integer range 0..100. Controls how profiles intersect in connections and corners of building elements A profile from one element protrudes into (i.e. displaces) a profile from another element in a joint of these elements if the former elements profile has higher priority than the latter. The priority value for a material profile in an element has to be set and maintained by software applications in relation to the material profiles in connected elements.

IfcMaterialProfileSet.Definition: The Ifc Material Profile Set is a designation by which individual material(s) of a prismatic element (for example, beam or column) constructed of a single or multiple material profiles is known.
IfcMaterialProfileSet.Name: Material Profile Set

Description.name: Description
Description.Definition: Definition of the material profile set in descriptive terms.

Name.name: Name
Name.Definition: The name by which the material profile set is known.

IfcMaterialProfileWithOffsets.Definition: Ifc Material Profile With Offsets is a specialization of Ifc Material Profile with additional longitudinal offsets .Relative positions of Ifc Material Profile With Offsets in the longitudinal direction of an element can be defined giving offsets at the start at the end, or at start and end. This shall not be used for relative positions of individual profiles in the plane of profile definition, which is given in composite profile definition itself. Also, care should be taken especially when used with Ifc Material Profile Set Usage Tapering for correct start and end offset assignment.
IfcMaterialProfileWithOffsets.Name: Material Profile With Offsets

OffsetValues.name: Offset Values
OffsetValues.Definition: The numerical value of profile offset, in the direction of the axis direction - always AXIS1 that is, the axis along the extrusion path. The Offset Values1 identifies the offset from the lower position along the axis direction (normally the start of the standard extrusion), the Offset Values2 identifies the offset from the upper position along the axis direction (normally the end of the standard extrusion).

IfcFireSuppressionTerminal.Definition: A fire suppression terminal has the purpose of delivering a fluid (gas or liquid) that will suppress a fire.A fire suppression terminal provides for all forms of sprinkler, spreader and other form of terminal that is connected to a pipework system and intended to act in the role of suppressing a fire.
IfcFireSuppressionTerminal.Name: Fire Suppression Terminal

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: Status of the element, predominately used in renovation or retrofitting projects. The status can be assigned to as New - element designed as new addition, Existing - element exists and remains, Demolish - element existed but is to be demolished, Temporary - element will exists only temporary (like a temporary support structure).

GrossWeight.name: Gross Weight
GrossWeight.Definition: Total Gross Weight of the object without any add-on parts and not taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

IfcFireSuppressionTerminalType.Definition: The flow terminal type Ifc Fire Suppression Terminal Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of fire suppression terminals. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcFireSuppressionTerminalType.Name: Fire Suppression Terminal Type

IfcInterceptor.Definition: An interceptor is a device designed and installed in order to separate and retain deleterious, hazardous or undesirable matter while permitting normal sewage or liquids to discharge into a collection system by gravity.
IfcInterceptor.Name: Interceptor

CoverLength.name: Cover Length
CoverLength.Definition: The length measured along the x-axis in the local coordinate system or the radius (in the case of a circular shape in plan) of the cover of the object.

CoverWidth.name: Cover Width
CoverWidth.Definition: The length measured along the y-axis in the local coordinate system of the cover of the object.

NominalBodyDepth.name: Nominal Body Depth
NominalBodyDepth.Definition: Nominal or quoted length measured along the z-axis of the local coordinate system of the object.

NominalBodyLength.name: Nominal Body Length
NominalBodyLength.Definition: Nominal or quoted length measured along the x-axis of the local coordinate system of the object.

NominalBodyWidth.name: Nominal Body Width
NominalBodyWidth.Definition: Nominal or quoted length, measured along the y-axis of the local coordinate system of the object.

OutletConnectionSize.name: Outlet Connection Size
OutletConnectionSize.Definition: Size of the outlet connection from the object.

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

The status can be assigned to as New - element designed as new addition, Existing - element exists and remains, Demolish - element existed but is to be demolished, Temporary - element will exists only temporary (like a temporary support structure).

GrossWeight.name: Gross Weight
GrossWeight.Definition: Total Gross Weight of the object without any add-on parts and not taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

IfcInterceptorType.Definition: The flow treatment device type Ifc Interceptor Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of interceptors. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcInterceptorType.Name: Interceptor Type

IfcSanitaryTerminal.Definition: A sanitary terminal is a fixed appliance or terminal usually supplied with water and used for drinking, cleaning or foul water disposal or that is an item of equipment directly used with such an appliance or terminal.
IfcSanitaryTerminal.Name: Sanitary Terminal

NominalLength.name: Nominal Length
NominalLength.Definition: The nominal overall length of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

NominalWidth.name: Nominal Width
NominalWidth.Definition: The nominal overall width of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcStackTerminal.Definition: A stack terminal is placed at the top of a ventilating stack (such as to prevent ingress by birds or rainwater) or rainwater pipe (to act as a collector or hopper for discharge from guttering).
IfcStackTerminal.Name: Stack Terminal

IfcWasteTerminal.Definition: A waste terminal has the purpose of collecting or intercepting waste from one or more sanitary terminals or other fluid waste generating equipment and discharging it into a single wastedrainage system.A waste terminal provides for all forms of trap and waste point that collects discharge from a sanitary terminal and discharges it into a wastedrainage subsystem or that collects waste from several terminals and passes it into a single wastedrainage subsystem. This includes the P and S traps from soil sanitary terminals, sinks, and basins as well as floor wastes and gully traps that provide collection points.
IfcWasteTerminal.Name: Waste Terminal

GrossWeight.name: Gross Weight
GrossWeight.Definition: Total Gross Weight of the object without any add-on parts and not taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

IfcWasteTerminalType.Definition: The flow terminal type Ifc Waste Terminal Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of waste terminals. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcWasteTerminalType.Name: Qtowaste Terminal Base Quantities

IfcConveyorSegment.Definition: A conveyor segment defines an occurrence of a flow segment continuous run within a conveyor system that joins two sections of the system. these can utilise different carrying methods such as belt, rope, chain, screw etc.
IfcConveyorSegment.Name: Conveyor Segment

IfcConveyorSegmentType.Definition: The Ifc Conveyor Segment Type provides the type information for Ifc Conveyor Segment occurrences.
IfcConveyorSegmentType.Name: Conveyor Segment Type

IfcLiquidTerminal.Definition: A liquid terminal is a terminating or origination point for the transfer of liquid between distribution system(s). this is the point where the liquid distribution system interacts with the external environment. An example of this is a loading arm for the transfer of liquid from a docked vessel.
IfcLiquidTerminal.Name: Liquid Terminal

IfcLiquidTerminalType.Definition: The Liquid Terminal Type provides the type information for Liquid Terminal occurrences.
IfcLiquidTerminalType.Name: Liquid Terminal Type

IfcMarineFacility.Definition: A marine facility represents any major structure or entity that is specific to the ports and waterways domain. examples of this include quays, jetties, shipyards, breakwaters etc.
IfcMarineFacility.Name: Marine Facility

BerthCargoWeight.name: Berth Cargo Weight
BerthCargoWeight.Definition: Total cargo weight of berths within the facility

Berths.name: Berths
Berths.Definition: Number of standard berths within the facility

Width.name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcMooringDevice.Definition: A mooring device is an active or passive built element whos primary function is to participate in the mooring of a vessel, this could be in the form of a bollard used as an attachment point for lines or active equipment such as quick release hooks.
IfcMooringDevice.Name: Mooring Device

MaximumLineCount.name: Maximum Line Count
MaximumLineCount.Definition: Maximum number of lines that may be secured to the mooring device.

MaximumLineSlope.name: Maximum Line Slope
MaximumLineSlope.Definition: Maximum allowable line angle in degrees (negative if below horizontal from quay)

MinumumLineSlope.name: Minumum Line Slope
MinumumLineSlope.Definition: Minimum allowable line angle in degrees (negative if below horizontal from quay)

IfcMooringDeviceType.Definition: The Ifc Mooring Device Type provides the type information for Ifc Mooring Device occurrences.
IfcMooringDeviceType.Name: Mooring Device Type

IfcNavigationElement.Definition: A navigation element is an active or passive built element whos primary function is to provide navigational instructions and warnings to vessels, this could be in the form of a floating buoy, a fixed beacon.
IfcNavigationElement.Name: Navigation Element

IfcNavigationElementType.Definition: The Ifc Navigation Element Type provides the type information for Ifc Navigation Element occurrences.
IfcNavigationElementType.Name: Qtovehicle Base Quantities

IfcEvent.Definition: An Ifc Event is something that happens that triggers an action or response.
IfcEvent.Name: Event

EventTriggerType.Definition: Identifies the predefined types of event trigger from which the type required may be set.

UserDefinedEventTriggerType.name: User Defined Event Trigger Type
UserDefinedEventTriggerType.Definition: A user defined event trigger type, the value of which is asserted when the value of an event trigger type is declared as USERDEFINED.

IfcProcedure.Definition: An Ifc Procedure is a logical set of actions to be taken in response to an event or to cause an event to occur.
IfcProcedure.Name: Procedure

IfcRelSequence.Definition: Ifc Rel Sequence is a sequential relationship between processes where one process must occur before the other in time and where the timing of the relationship may be described as a type of sequence. The relating process (Ifc Rel Sequence.Relating Process) is considered to be the predecessor in the relationship (has precedence) whilst the related process (Ifc Rel Sequence.Related Process) is the successor.Ifc Rel Sequence is defined as one-to-one relationship therefore it assigns one predecessor to one successor.
IfcRelSequence.Name: Rel Sequence

SequenceType.Definition: The way in which the time lag applies to the sequence.

UserDefinedSequenceType.name: User Defined Sequence Type
UserDefinedSequenceType.Definition: Allows for specification of user defined type of the sequence beyond the enumeration values (STARTSTART, STARTFINISH FINISHSTART, FINISHFINISH) provided by Sequence Type attribute of type Ifc Sequence Enum. When a value is provided for attribute User Defined Sequence Type in parallel the attribute Sequence Type shall have enumeration value USERDEFINED. IFC4 CHANGE Attribute added

IfcTask.Definition: An Ifc Task is an identifiable unit of work to be carried out in a construction project.A task is typically used to describe an activity for the construction or installation of products, but is not limited to these types. For example it might be used to describe design processes, move operations and other design, construction and operation related activities as well.Quantities of resources consumed by the task are dealt with by defining the Ifc Element Quantity for the resource and not at the instance of Ifc Task.
IfcTask.Name: Task

IsMilestone.name: Is Milestone
IsMilestone.Definition: Identifies whether a task is a milestone task ( TRUE) or not ( FALSE).

Priority.name: Priority
Priority.Definition: A value that indicates the relative priority of the task (in comparison to the priorities of other tasks).

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: Current status of the task.

WorkMethod.name: Work Method
WorkMethod.Definition: The method of work used in carrying out a task.

IfcTaskType.Definition: An Ifc Task Type defines a particular type of task that may be specified for use within a work control.
IfcTaskType.Name: Task Type

IfcWorkCalendar.Definition: An Ifc Work Calendar defines working and non-working time periods for tasks and resources. It enables to define both specific time periods, such as from 700 till 1200 on 25th August 2009, as well as repetitive time periods based on frequently used recurrence patterns, such as each Monday from 700 till 1200 between 1st March 2009 and 31st December 2009.
IfcWorkCalendar.Name: Work Calendar

IfcWorkControl.Definition: An Ifc Work Control is an abstract supertype which captures information that is common to both Ifc Work Plan and Ifc Work Schedule.
IfcWorkControl.Name: Work Control

WorkDayDuration.name: Work Day Duration
WorkDayDuration.Definition: The elapsed time within a worktime-based day. For presentation purposes, applications may choose to display Ifc Task durations in work days where Ifc Task Time.Duration TypeWORKTIME. This value must be less than or equal to 24 hours (an elapsed day) if omitted then 8 hours is assumed.

WorkFinishTime.name: Work Finish Time
WorkFinishTime.Definition: The default time of day a task is scheduled to finish. For presentation purposes, if the finish time of a task matches the Work Finish Time, then applications may choose to display the date only. Conversely when entering dates without specifying time, applications may automatically append the Work Finish Time.

WorkMonthDuration.name: Work Month Duration
WorkMonthDuration.Definition: The elapsed time within a worktime-based month. For presentation purposes, applications may choose to display Ifc Task durations in work months where Ifc Task Time.Duration TypeWORKTIME. This value must be less than or equal to 744 hours (an elapsed month of 31 days) if omitted then 160 hours is assumed.

WorkStartTime.name: Work Start Time
WorkStartTime.Definition: The default time of day a task is scheduled to start. For presentation purposes, if the start time of a task matches the Work Start Time, then applications may choose to display the date only. Conversely when entering dates without specifying time, applications may automatically append the Work Start Time.

WorkWeekDuration.name: Work Week Duration
WorkWeekDuration.Definition: The elapsed time within a worktime-based week. For presentation purposes, applications may choose to display Ifc Task durations in work weeks where Ifc Task Time.Duration TypeWORKTIME. This value must be less than or equal to 168 hours (an elapsed week) if omitted then 40 hours is assumed.

CreationDate.name: Creation Date
CreationDate.Definition: The date that the plan is created.

Duration.name: Duration
Duration.Definition: The total duration of the entire work schedule.

FinishTime.name: Finish Time
FinishTime.Definition: The finish time of the schedule.

Purpose.name: Purpose
Purpose.Definition: A description of the purpose of the work schedule.

StartTime.name: Start Time
StartTime.Definition: The start time of the schedule.

TotalFloat.name: Total Float
TotalFloat.Definition: The total time float of the entire work schedule.

IfcWorkPlan.Definition: An Ifc Work Plan represents work plans in a construction or a facilities management project.
IfcWorkPlan.Name: Work Plan

IfcWorkSchedule.Definition: An Ifc Work Schedule represents a task schedule of a work plan, which in turn can contain a set of schedules for different purposes.
IfcWorkSchedule.Name: Work Control Common

IfcAlignment.Definition: For the purposes of IFC the English term alignment defines three separate but closely interconnected concepts.definition of a reference system for linear positioning
IfcAlignment.Name: Alignment

LRMConstraint.name: Lrmconstraint
LRMConstraint.Definition: Allows for the specification of constraints imposed by this Linear Referencing Method. For example, a Reference Post Linear Referencing Method may specify that referents be of type reference marker.

LRMName.name: Lrmname
LRMName.Definition: Gives the name of this Linear Referencing Method, such as kilometre-point.

LRMType.name: Lrmtype
LRMType.Definition: Gives the type of this Linear Referencing Method.

LRMUnit.name: Lrmunit
LRMUnit.Definition: Specifies the units of measure used by this Linear Referencing Method for measures along the linear element being measured.

UserDefinedLRMType.name: User Defined Lrmtype
UserDefinedLRMType.Definition: Gives the user defined type of this Linear Referencing Method when property LRMType is LRMUSERDEFINED.

IfcAlignmentCant.Definition: An Ifc Alignment Cant is a lateral inclination profile defined along the horizontal alignment. All points defined in this profile have two coordinate values. The first value is the distance along the horizontal alignment, and the second value is the height relative to the projection of the point along vertical alignment.Cant as a railway specificity
IfcAlignmentCant.Name: Alignment Cant

RailHeadDistance.name: Rail Head Distance
RailHeadDistance.Definition: Length measured as distance between the nominal centre points of the two contact patches of a wheelset and rails.

IfcAlignmentHorizontal.Definition: An Ifc Alignment Horizontal is a linear reference projected onto the horizontal xy plane. Points along a horizontal alignment have two coordinate values, x and y in the local Cartesian engineering system.The horizontal alignment is defined by segments that are connected end-to-start. The transition at the segment connection is not enforced to be tangential, if the tangential continuity flag is set to false, otherwise a tangential continuity shall be preserved. Based on the context of the project, they are geo-referenced and convertible into Northing and Easting values.
IfcAlignmentHorizontal.Name: Alignment Horizontal

IfcAlignmentSegment.Definition: An Ifc Alignment Segment is a segment of an Ifc Alignment where either the vertical or horizontal direction or cant (in the case of trackdesign) obey a unique mathematical description as a function of the horizontal projection segment length of the alignment.
IfcAlignmentSegment.Name: Alignment Segment

CantDeficiency.name: Cant Deficiency
CantDeficiency.Definition: Difference between applied cant and a higher equilibrium cant.

CantEquilibrium.name: Cant Equilibrium
CantEquilibrium.Definition: Cant at a particular speed at which the vehicle will have a resultant force perpendicular to the running plane.

EndSmoothingLength.name: End Smoothing Length
EndSmoothingLength.Definition: Length for the circular transition change of curvature at the end of the cant segment, measured from the start of the circular transition change of curvature to the end of the cant segment.

StartSmoothingLength.name: Start Smoothing Length
StartSmoothingLength.Definition: Length for the circular transition change of curvature at the start of the cant segment, measured from the start of the cant segment to the end of the circular transition change of curvature.

EndElevation.name: End Elevation
EndElevation.Definition: Elevation of the end point relative to the mean sea level.

StartElevation.name: Start Elevation
StartElevation.Definition: Elevation of the start point relative to the mean sea level.

IfcAlignmentVertical.Definition: An Ifc Alignment Vertical is a height profile along the horizontal alignment. Points along a vertical alignment have two coordinate values. The first value is the distance along the horizontal alignment, the second value is the height according to the project engineering coordinate system. Based on the context of the project, they are georeferenced and the height value is convertible into orthogonal height abovebelow the vertical datum.
IfcAlignmentVertical.Name: Alignment Vertical

IfcAnnotation.Definition: An annotation is an information element within the geometric (and spatial) context of a project, that adds a note or meaning to the objects which constitutes the project model. Annotations include additional points, curves, text, dimensioning, hatching and other forms of graphical notes. It also includes virtual or symbolic representations of additional model components, not representing products or spatial structures, such as survey points and lines, contour lines or similar.
IfcAnnotation.Name: Annotation

RoadVisibleDistanceLeft.name: Road Visible Distance Left
RoadVisibleDistanceLeft.Definition: Distance visible to the left of the access.

RoadVisibleDistanceRight.name: Road Visible Distance Right
RoadVisibleDistanceRight.Definition: Distance visible to the right of the access.

SetbackDistance.name: Setback Distance
SetbackDistance.Definition: Setback distance from the point of connection on the major element along the axis of the minor element (e.g. distance from a public road at which the line of sigfht is measured.

VisibleAngleLeft.name: Visible Angle Left
VisibleAngleLeft.Definition: Angle of visibility to the left of the access.

VisibleAngleRight.name: Visible Angle Right
VisibleAngleRight.Definition: Angle of visibility to the right of the access.

SoundFrequency.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SoundFrequency.name: Sound Frequency
SoundFrequency.Definition: List of nominal sound frequencies, correlated to the Sound Pressure time series values (Ifc Time Series.List Values)

SoundPressure.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SoundPressure.name: Sound Pressure
SoundPressure.Definition: A time series of sound pressure values measured in decibels at a reference pressure of 20 micro Pascals for the referenced octave band frequency. Each value in Ifc Time Series.List Values is correlated to the sound frequency at the same position within Sound Frequencies.

SoundScale.name: Sound Scale
SoundScale.Definition: The reference sound scale.DBA Decibels in an A-weighted scale

IfcBridge.Definition: A Bridge is a civil engineering work that affords passage to pedestrians, animals, vehicles, and services above obstacles or between two points at a height above ground.
IfcBridge.Name: Bridge

StructureIndicator.name: Structure Indicator
StructureIndicator.Definition: The type of bridge structure (composite, coated, homogeneous or other)

IfcBuilding.Definition: A building represents a structure that provides shelter for its occupants or contents and stands in one place. The building is also used to provide a basic element within the spatial structure hierarchy for the components of a building project (together with site, storey, and space).
IfcBuilding.Name: Building

AddressLines.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AddressLines.name: Address Lines

Country.name: Country
Country.Definition: The two letter country code (from ISO 3166).

ElectronicMailAddresses.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ElectronicMailAddresses.name: Electronic Mail Addresses
ElectronicMailAddresses.Definition: The list of Email addresses at which Email messages may be received.

FacsimileNumbers.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
FacsimileNumbers.name: Facsimile Numbers
FacsimileNumbers.Definition: The list of fax numbers at which fax messages may be received.

InternalLocation.name: Internal Location
InternalLocation.Definition: An organization defined address for internal mail delivery.

MessagingIDs.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
MessagingIDs.name: Messaging Ids
MessagingIDs.Definition: IDs or addresses for any other means of telecommunication, for example instant messaging, voice-over-IP, or file transfer protocols. The communication protocol is indicated by the URI value with scheme designations such as irc, sip, or ftp.

PagerNumber.name: Pager Number
PagerNumber.Definition: The pager number at which paging messages may be received.

PostalBox.name: Postal Box
PostalBox.Definition: An address that is implied by an identifiable mail drop.

PostalCode.name: Postal Code
PostalCode.Definition: The code that is used by the countrys postal service.

Purpose.name: Purpose
Purpose.Definition: Indication of the purpose of this object

TelephoneNumbers.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TelephoneNumbers.name: Telephone Numbers
TelephoneNumbers.Definition: The list of telephone numbers at which telephone messages may be received.

UserDefinedPurpose.name: User Defined Purpose
UserDefinedPurpose.Definition: Allows for specification of user specific purpose of the address beyond the enumeration values provided by Purpose attribute of type Ifc Address Type Enum. When a value is provided for attribute User Defined Purpose, in parallel the attribute Purpose shall have enumeration value USERDEFINED.

WWWHomePageURL.name: Wwwhome Page Url
WWWHomePageURL.Definition: The world wide web address at which the preliminary page of information for the person or organization can be located.

BuildingID.name: Building Id
BuildingID.Definition: A unique identifier assigned to a building. A temporary identifier is initially assigned at the time of making a planning application. This temporary identifier is changed to a permanent identifier when the building is registered into a statutory buildings and properties database.

ConstructionMethod.name: Construction Method
ConstructionMethod.Definition: The type of construction action to the object, e.g. new construction, renovation, refurbishment, etc.

ElevationOfRefHeight.name: Elevation of Ref Height
ElevationOfRefHeight.Definition: Elevation above sea level of the reference height used for all storey elevation measures, equals to height 0.0. It is usually the ground floor level.

ElevationOfTerrain.name: Elevation of Terrain
ElevationOfTerrain.Definition: Elevation above the minimal terrain level around the foot print of the building, given in elevation above sea level.

FireProtectionClass.name: Fire Protection Class
FireProtectionClass.Definition: Main fire protection class for the building which is assigned from the fire protection classification table as given by the relevant national building code.

GrossPlannedArea.name: Gross Planned Area
GrossPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned gross area of the spatial structure element. Used for programming the spatial structure element.

IsLandmarked.name: Is Landmarked
IsLandmarked.Definition: This builing is listed as a historic building (TRUE), or not (FALSE), or unknown.

IsPermanentID.name: Is Permanent Id
IsPermanentID.Definition: Indicates whether the identity assigned to the object is permanent ( TRUE) or temporary (FALSE).

NetPlannedArea.name: Net Planned Area
NetPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned net area of the object. Used for programming the object.

NumberOfStoreys.name: Number of Storeys
NumberOfStoreys.Definition: The number of storeys within a building.

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

SprinklerProtection.name: Sprinkler Protection
SprinklerProtection.Definition: Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.name: Sprinkler Protection Automatic
SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.Definition: Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

YearOfConstruction.name: Year of Construction
YearOfConstruction.Definition: Year of construction of this building, including expected year of completion.

YearOfLastRefurbishment.name: Year of Last Refurbishment
YearOfLastRefurbishment.Definition: Year of last major refurbishment, or reconstruction, of the building (applies to reconstruction works).

MarketCategory.name: Market Category
MarketCategory.Definition: Category of use e.g. residential, commercial, recreation etc.

MarketSubCategoriesAvailableFuture.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
MarketSubCategoriesAvailableFuture.name: Market Sub Categories Available Future
MarketSubCategoriesAvailableFuture.Definition: A list of the sub categories of property that are expected to be available in the future expressed in terms of Ifc Label.

MarketSubCategoriesAvailableNow.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
MarketSubCategoriesAvailableNow.name: Market Sub Categories Available Now
MarketSubCategoriesAvailableNow.Definition: A list of the sub categories of property that are currently available expressed in terms of Ifc Label.

MarketSubCategory.name: Market Sub Category
MarketSubCategory.Definition: Subset of category of use e.g. multi-family, 2 bedroom, low rise.

NarrativeText.name: Narrative Text
NarrativeText.Definition: Added information relating to the adjacent building use that is not appropriate to the general descriptive text associated with an entity through the inherited Ifc Root.Description.

PlanningControlStatus.name: Planning Control Status
PlanningControlStatus.Definition: Label of zoning category or class, or planning control category for the site or facility.

RentalRatesInCategoryFuture.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RentalRatesInCategoryFuture.name: Rental Rates In Category Future
RentalRatesInCategoryFuture.Definition: Range of the cost rates for property expected to be available in the future in the required category.

RentalRatesInCategoryNow.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RentalRatesInCategoryNow.name: Rental Rates In Category Now
RentalRatesInCategoryNow.Definition: Range of the cost rates for property currently available in the required category.

TenureModesAvailableFuture.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TenureModesAvailableFuture.name: Tenure Modes Available Future
TenureModesAvailableFuture.Definition: A list of the tenure modes that are expected to be available in the future expressed in terms of Ifc Label.

TenureModesAvailableNow.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TenureModesAvailableNow.name: Tenure Modes Available Now
TenureModesAvailableNow.Definition: A list of the tenure modes that are currently available expressed in terms of Ifc Label.

VacancyRateInCategoryFuture.name: Vacancy Rate In Category Future
VacancyRateInCategoryFuture.Definition: Percentage of vacancy found in the particular category expected in the future.

VacancyRateInCategoryNow.name: Vacancy Rate In Category Now
VacancyRateInCategoryNow.Definition: Percentage of vacancy found in the particular category currently.

MarketCategory.name: Market Category
MarketCategory.Definition: Category of use e.g. residential, commercial, recreation etc.

MarketSubCategory.name: Market Sub Category
MarketSubCategory.Definition: Subset of category of use e.g. multi-family, 2 bedroom, low rise.

NarrativeText.name: Narrative Text
NarrativeText.Definition: Added information relating to the adjacent building use that is not appropriate to the general descriptive text associated with an entity through the inherited Ifc Root.Description.

PlanningControlStatus.name: Planning Control Status
PlanningControlStatus.Definition: Label of zoning category or class, or planning control category for the site or facility.

EavesHeight.name: Eaves Height
EavesHeight.Definition: Standard net height of this storey, from the top surface of the construction floor, to the bottom surface of the construction floor or roof above. Only provided is there is a constant height.

FootPrintArea.name: Foot Print Area
FootPrintArea.Definition: Gross area of the site covered by the building(s).

GrossFloorArea.name: Gross Floor Area
GrossFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all gross floor areas within the spatial structure element.

GrossVolume.name: Gross Volume
GrossVolume.Definition: Total gross volume of the object. Openings, recesses, enclosed objects and projections are not taken into account.

NetFloorArea.name: Net Floor Area
NetFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all net usable floor areas.

NetVolume.name: Net Volume
NetVolume.Definition: Total net volume of the object, taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

BuildingThermalExposure.name: Building Thermal Exposure
BuildingThermalExposure.Definition: The thermal exposure expected by the building based on surrounding site conditions.

CoolingDesignDay.name: Cooling Design Day
CoolingDesignDay.Definition: The month, day and time that has been selected for the cooling design calculations.

CoolingDryBulb.name: Cooling Dry Bulb
CoolingDryBulb.Definition: Dry bulb temperature, usually for for cooling design.

CoolingWetBulb.name: Cooling Wet Bulb
CoolingWetBulb.Definition: Outside wet bulb temperature for cooling design.

HeatingDesignDay.name: Heating Design Day
HeatingDesignDay.Definition: The month, day and time that has been selected for the heating design calculations.

HeatingDryBulb.name: Heating Dry Bulb
HeatingDryBulb.Definition: Dry bulb temperature for heating design.

HeatingWetBulb.name: Heating Wet Bulb
HeatingWetBulb.Definition: Outside wet bulb temperature for heating design.

PrevailingWindDirection.name: Prevailing Wind Direction
PrevailingWindDirection.Definition: The prevailing wind angle direction measured from True North (0 degrees) in a clockwise direction.

PrevailingWindVelocity.name: Prevailing Wind Velocity
PrevailingWindVelocity.Definition: The design wind velocity coming from the direction specified by the Prevailing Wind Direction attribute.

WeatherDataDate.name: Weather Data Date
WeatherDataDate.Definition: The date for which the weather data was gathered.

WeatherDataStation.name: Weather Data Station
WeatherDataStation.Definition: The site weather data station description or reference to the data source from which weather data was obtained for use in calculations.

Electricity.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Electricity.name: Electricity
Electricity.Definition: The amount of electricity consumed during the period specified in the time series.

Fuel.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Fuel.name: Fuel
Fuel.Definition: The amount of fuel consumed during the period specified in the time series.

Heat.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Heat.name: Heat
Heat.Definition: The amount of heat energy consumed during the period specified in the time series.

Steam.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Steam.name: Steam
Steam.Definition: The amount of steam consumed during the period specified in the time series.

Water.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Water.name: Water
Water.Definition: The amount of water consumed during the period specified in the time series.

ElevationOfRefHeight.name: Elevation of Ref Height
ElevationOfRefHeight.Definition: Elevation above sea level of the reference height used for all storey elevation measures, equals to height 0.0. It is usually the ground floor level.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION This attribute is deprecated and shall no longer be used.

ElevationOfTerrain.name: Elevation of Terrain
ElevationOfTerrain.Definition: Elevation above the minimal terrain level around the foot print of the building, given in elevation above sea level.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION This attribute is deprecated and shall no longer be used.

IfcBuildingStorey.Definition: The building storey has an elevation and typically represents a (nearly) horizontal aggregation of spaces that are vertically bound.
IfcBuildingStorey.Name: Building Storey

AboveGround.name: Above Ground
AboveGround.Definition: Indication whether this building storey is fully above ground (TRUE), or below ground (FALSE), or partially above and below ground (UNKNOWN) - as in sloped terrain.

ElevationOfFFLRelative.name: Elevation of Fflrelative
ElevationOfFFLRelative.Definition: Elevation of the top surface of the finished floor level given in elevation above the local zero height. If the level varies and there is no significantly more prominent elevation, then this property may be omitted. In case of any inconsistency with the geometric positioning of the top surface, the geometric representation takes precedence.

ElevationOfSSLRelative.name: Elevation of Sslrelative
ElevationOfSSLRelative.Definition: Elevation of the top surface of the structural slab level given in elevation above the local zero height. If the level varies and there is no significantly more prominent elevation, then this property may be omitted. In case of any inconsistency with the geometric positioning of the top surface, the geometric representation takes precedence.

EntranceLevel.name: Entrance Level
EntranceLevel.Definition: Indication whether this building storey is an entrance level to the building (TRUE), or (FALSE) if otherwise.

GrossPlannedArea.name: Gross Planned Area
GrossPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned gross area of the spatial structure element. Used for programming the spatial structure element.

LoadBearingCapacity.name: Load Bearing Capacity
LoadBearingCapacity.Definition: Maximum load bearing capacity of the floor structure throughtout the storey as designed.

NetPlannedArea.name: Net Planned Area
NetPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned net area of the object. Used for programming the object.

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

SprinklerProtection.name: Sprinkler Protection
SprinklerProtection.Definition: Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.name: Sprinkler Protection Automatic
SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.Definition: Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

GrossFloorArea.name: Gross Floor Area
GrossFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all gross floor areas within the spatial structure element.

GrossHeight.name: Gross Height
GrossHeight.Definition: Standard gross height of this storey, from the top surface of the construction floor, to the top surface of the construction floor or roof above. Only provided is there is a constant height.

GrossPerimeter.name: Gross Perimeter
GrossPerimeter.Definition: Gross perimeter at the outer contour of the object.

GrossVolume.name: Gross Volume
GrossVolume.Definition: Total gross volume of the object. Openings, recesses, enclosed objects and projections are not taken into account.

NetFloorArea.name: Net Floor Area
NetFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all net usable floor areas.

NetHeight.name: Net Height
NetHeight.Definition: Standard net height of this storey, from the top surface of the construction floor, to the bottom surface of the construction floor or roof above. Only provided is there is a constant height.

NetVolume.name: Net Volume
NetVolume.Definition: Total net volume of the object, taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

Elevation.name: Elevation
Elevation.Definition: Elevation of the base of this storey, relative to the 0,00 internal reference height of the building. The 0.00 level is given by the absolute above sea level height by the Elevation Of Ref Height attribute given at Ifc Building.

IfcBuiltElement.Definition: The built element comprises all elements that are primarily part of the construction of a built facility, i.e., its structural and space separating system. Built elements are all physically existent and tangible things.This Ifc Built Element is a generalization of all elements that are major functional parts of the structural or space separation system of a built facility. Typical examples of Ifc Built Element entities are (among others)built elements within a space separation system
IfcBuiltElement.Name: Built Element

IfcBuiltElementType.Definition: The Ifc Built Element Type provides the type information for Ifc Built Element occurrences.
IfcBuiltElementType.Name: Built Element Type

IfcBuiltSystem.Definition: A built system is a group by which built elements are grouped according to a common function within the facility.The group Ifc Built System defines the occurrence of a specialized system for use within the context of a facilities physical or finishing fabric. Important functionalities for the description of a built system are derived from supertypesFrom Ifc System it inherits the ability to couple the built system via Ifc Rel Referenced In Spatial Structure to one or more Ifc Spatial Element subtypes as necessary.
IfcBuiltSystem.Name: Built System

DownstreamConnections.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
DownstreamConnections.name: Downstream Connections
DownstreamConnections.Definition: Names of downstream connected equipment and spaces, if not otherwise represented

ProcessCapacity.name: Process Capacity
ProcessCapacity.Definition: The number of units that can be processed in the time defined in Process Performance

ProcessItem.name: Process Item
ProcessItem.Definition: The type of item (and its measurement method) being modelled within a process. This can be cargo, passengers or vehicles that pass through the system.

ProcessPerformance.name: Process Performance
ProcessPerformance.Definition: Minimum time to accept or dispatch the entire item capacity.

UpstreamConnections.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
UpstreamConnections.name: Upstream Connections
UpstreamConnections.Definition: Names of upstream connected equipment and spaces, if not otherwise represented

LongName.name: Long Name
LongName.Definition: Long name for a built system, used for informal purposes. It should be used, if available, in conjunction with the inherited Name attribute.

IfcCivilElement.Definition: An Ifc Civil Element is a generalization of all elements within a civil engineering works that cannot be represented as Building Elements, Distribution Elements or Geographic Elements. Depending on the context of the construction project, included building work, such as buildings or factories, are represented as a collection of Ifc Built Elements, distribution systems, such as piping or drainage, are represented as a collection of Ifc Distribution Elements, and other geographic elements, such as trees, light posts, traffic signs etc. are represented as Ifc Geographic Elements.
IfcCivilElement.Name: Civil Element

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: Status of the element, predominately used in renovation or retrofitting projects. The status can be assigned to as New - element designed as new addition, Existing - element exists and remains, Demolish - element existed but is to be demolished, Temporary - element will exists only temporary (like a temporary support structure).

AssemblyPlace.name: Assembly Place
AssemblyPlace.Definition: Enumeration defining where the assembly is intended to take place, either in a factory, other offsite location or on the building site.

CastingMethod.name: Casting Method
CastingMethod.Definition: The method of casting the concrete into its designed form.

ConcreteCover.name: Concrete Cover
ConcreteCover.Definition: The protective concrete cover at the reinforcing bars according to local building regulations.

ConcreteCoverAtLinks.name: Concrete Cover At Links
ConcreteCoverAtLinks.Definition: The protective concrete cover at the reinforcement links according to local building regulations.

ConcreteCoverAtMainBars.name: Concrete Cover At Main Bars
ConcreteCoverAtMainBars.Definition: The protective concrete cover at the main reinforcing bars according to local building regulations.

ConstructionToleranceClass.name: Construction Tolerance Class
ConstructionToleranceClass.Definition: Classification designation of the on-site construction tolerances according to local standards.

DimensionalAccuracyClass.name: Dimensional Accuracy Class
DimensionalAccuracyClass.Definition: Classification designation of the dimensional accuracy requirement according to local standards.

ExposureClass.name: Exposure Class
ExposureClass.Definition: Classification of exposure to environmental conditions, usually specified in accordance with the concrete design code which is applied in the project.

ReinforcementAreaRatio.name: Reinforcement Area Ratio
ReinforcementAreaRatio.Definition: The required ratio of the effective area of the reinforcement to the effective area of the concrete At any section of a reinforced concrete structural element.

ReinforcementStrengthClass.name: Reinforcement Strength Class
ReinforcementStrengthClass.Definition: Classification of the reinforcement strength in accordance with the concrete design code which is applied in the project. The reinforcing strength class often combines strength and ductility.

ReinforcementVolumeRatio.name: Reinforcement Volume Ratio
ReinforcementVolumeRatio.Definition: The required ratio of the effective mass of the reinforcement to the effective volume of the concrete of a reinforced concrete structural element.

StrengthClass.name: Strength Class
StrengthClass.Definition: Classification of the concrete strength in accordance with the concrete design code which is applied in the project.

StructuralClass.name: Structural Class
StructuralClass.Definition: The structural class defined for the concrete structure (e.g. 1).

AsBuiltLocationNumber.name: As Built Location Number
AsBuiltLocationNumber.Definition: Defines a unique location within a structure, the slot into which the piece was installed. Where pieces share the same piece mark, they can be interchanged. The value is only known after erection.

PieceMark.name: Piece Mark
PieceMark.Definition: Defines a unique piece for production purposes. All pieces with the same piece mark value are identical and interchangeable. The piece mark may be composed of sub-parts that have specific locally defined meaning (e.g. B-1A may denote a beam, of generic type 1 and specific shape A).

SerialNumber.name: Serial Number
SerialNumber.Definition: The manufacturers serial number assigned to an occurrence of a product.

TypeDesignation.name: Type Designation
TypeDesignation.Definition: Type designator for the element. The content depends on local standards. Eg. Bull nose, Half batter, Dropper, Chamfer etc

BatterAtEnd.name: Batter At End
BatterAtEnd.Definition: The angle, in radians, by which the formwork at the ending face of a piece is to be rotated from the vertical in order to compensate for the rotation of the face that will occur once the piece is stripped from its form, inducing camber due to eccentric prestressing.

BatterAtStart.name: Batter At Start
BatterAtStart.Definition: The angle, in radians, by which the formwork at the starting face of a piece is to be rotated from the vertical in order to compensate for the rotation of the face that will occur once the piece is stripped from its form, inducing camber due to eccentric prestressing.

CamberAtMidspan.name: Camber At Midspan
CamberAtMidspan.Definition: The camber deflection, measured from the midpoint of a cambered face of a piece to the midpoint of the chord joining the ends of the same face, as shown in the figure below, divided by the original (nominal) straight length of the face of the piece.

CornerChamfer.name: Corner Chamfer
CornerChamfer.Definition: The chamfer in the corners of the precast element. The chamfer is presumed to be equal in both directions.

DesignLocationNumber.name: Design Location Number
DesignLocationNumber.Definition: Defines a unique location within a structure, the slot for which the piece was designed.

FormStrippingStrength.name: Form Stripping Strength
FormStrippingStrength.Definition: The minimum required compressive strength of the concrete at form stripping time.

HollowCorePlugging.name: Hollow Core Plugging
HollowCorePlugging.Definition: A descriptive label for how the hollow core ends are treated they may be left open, closed with a plug, or sealed with cast concrete. Values would be, for example Unplugged, Plugged, Sealed With Concrete. This property applies to hollow core slabs only.

InitialTension.name: Initial Tension
InitialTension.Definition: The initial stress of the tendon. This property applies to prestressed concrete elements only.

LiftingStrength.name: Lifting Strength
LiftingStrength.Definition: The minimum required compressive strength of the concrete when the concrete element is lifted.

ManufacturingToleranceClass.name: Manufacturing Tolerance Class
ManufacturingToleranceClass.Definition: Classification designation of the manufacturing tolerances according to local standards.

PieceMark.name: Piece Mark
PieceMark.Definition: Defines a unique piece for production purposes. All pieces with the same piece mark value are identical and interchangeable. The piece mark may be composed of sub-parts that have specific locally defined meaning (e.g. B-1A may denote a beam, of generic type 1 and specific shape A).

ReleaseStrength.name: Release Strength
ReleaseStrength.Definition: The minimum required compressive strength of the concrete when the tendon stress is released. This property applies to prestressed concrete elements only.

Shortening.name: Shortening
Shortening.Definition: The ratio of the distance by which a precast piece is shortened after release from its form (due to compression induced by prestressing) to its original (nominal) length.

SupportDuringTransportDescription.name: Support During Transport Description
SupportDuringTransportDescription.Definition: Textual description of how the concrete element is supported during transportation.

SupportDuringTransportDocReference.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SupportDuringTransportDocReference.name: Support During Transport Doc Reference
SupportDuringTransportDocReference.Definition: Reference to an external document defining how the concrete element is supported during transportation.

TendonRelaxation.name: Tendon Relaxation
TendonRelaxation.Definition: The maximum allowable relaxation of the tendon (usually expressed as 1000 h).This property applies to prestressed concrete elements only.

TransportationStrength.name: Transportation Strength
TransportationStrength.Definition: The minimum required compressive strength of the concrete required for transportation.

Twisting.name: Twisting
Twisting.Definition: The angle, in radians, through which the end face of a precast piece is rotated with respect to its starting face, along its longitudinal axis, as a result of non-aligned supports. This measure is also termed the warping angle.

TypeDesignation.name: Type Designation
TypeDesignation.Definition: Type designator for the element. The content depends on local standards. Eg. Bull nose, Half batter, Dropper, Chamfer etc

IfcCivilElementType.Definition: An Ifc Civil Element Type is used to define an element specification of an element used within civil engineering works. Civil element types include for different types of element that may be used to represent information for construction works external to a building. Ifc Civil Element Types may includelinear elements such as sections of a roadway (including carriagewaypavement, verge, median, marker line, kerb etc.)
IfcCivilElementType.Name: Civil Element Type

IfcDistributionElement.Definition: Ifc Distribution Element is a generalization of all elements that participate in a distribution system. Typical examples of Ifc Distribution Element entities are (among others)building service elements within a heating system
IfcDistributionElement.Name: Distribution Element

ConductorFunction.name: Conductor Function
ConductorFunction.Definition: Indicates function of the conductors to which the load is connected. Where L1, L2 and L3 represent the phase lines according to IEC 60446 notation (sometimes phase lines may be referenced by color Red, Blue, Yellow or by number 1, 2, 3 etc). Protective Earth is sometimes also known as CPC or common protective conductor. Note that for an electrical device, a set of line conductor functions may be applied.

EarthingStyle.name: Earthing Style
EarthingStyle.Definition: Indicates the earthing style of the electric device.

HasProtectiveEarth.name: Has Protective Earth
HasProtectiveEarth.Definition: Indicates whether the object has a protective earth connection (TRUE) or not ( FALSE).

HeatDissipation.name: Heat Dissipation
HeatDissipation.Definition: Indicates the heat dissipation of the electric device measured in power.

IK_Code.name: Ikcode
IK_Code.Definition: IK Code according to IEC 62262 (2002) is a numeric classification for the degree of protection provided by enclosures for electrical equipment against external mechanical impacts.

InsulationStandardClass.name: Insulation Standard Class
InsulationStandardClass.Definition: Insulation standard classes provides basic protection information against electric shock. Defines levels of insulation required in terms of constructional requirements (creepage and clearance distances) and electrical requirements (compliance with electric strength tests). Basic insulation is considered to be shorted under single fault conditions. The actual values required depend on the working voltage to which the insulation is subjected, as well as other factors. Also indicates whether the electrical device has a protective earth connection.

IP_Code.name: Ipcode
IP_Code.Definition: IP Code, the International Protection Marking, IEC 60529), classifies and rates the degree of protection provided against intrusion.

NominalFrequencyRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
NominalFrequencyRange.name: Nominal Frequency Range
NominalFrequencyRange.Definition: The upper and lower limits of frequency for which the operation of the device is certified.

NumberOfPoles.name: Number of Poles
NumberOfPoles.Definition: Number of poles that the object would affect.

NumberOfPowerSupplyPorts.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
NumberOfPowerSupplyPorts.name: Number of Power Supply Ports
NumberOfPowerSupplyPorts.Definition: Indicates the number of power supply ports of the electric device.

Power.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Power.name: Power
Power.Definition: The actual power and operable range.

RatedCurrent.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RatedCurrent.name: Rated Current
RatedCurrent.Definition: The current that a device is designed to handle.

RatedVoltage.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RatedVoltage.name: Rated Voltage
RatedVoltage.Definition: The range of allowed voltage that a device is certified to handle. The upper bound of this value is the maximum.

EnergyConversionEfficiency.name: Energy Conversion Efficiency
EnergyConversionEfficiency.Definition: Measure of the efficiency of conversion of fuel energy to mechanical energy

EnergySourceLabel.name: Energy Source Label
EnergySourceLabel.Definition: Type of energy source e.g. Electricity, Diesel, LPG etc. utilised by the element.

CarbonDioxideEmissions.name: Carbon Dioxide Emissions
CarbonDioxideEmissions.Definition: Rate of emission of carbon dioxide

NitrogenOxidesEmissions.name: Nitrogen Oxides Emissions
NitrogenOxidesEmissions.Definition: Rate of emission of nitrogen oxides

ParticulateMatterEmissions.name: Particulate Matter Emissions
ParticulateMatterEmissions.Definition: Rate of emission of particulate matter

SulphurDioxideEmissions.name: Sulphur Dioxide Emissions
SulphurDioxideEmissions.Definition: Rate of emission of sulphur dioxide

ElectroMagneticStandardsCompliance.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ElectroMagneticStandardsCompliance.name: Electro Magnetic Standards Compliance
ElectroMagneticStandardsCompliance.Definition: Information about compliance with regard to electro magnetic related standards.

ExplosiveAtmosphereStandardsCompliance.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ExplosiveAtmosphereStandardsCompliance.name: Explosive Atmosphere Standards Compliance
ExplosiveAtmosphereStandardsCompliance.Definition: Information about compliance with regard to explosive atmosphere related standards.

FireProofingStandardsCompliance.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
FireProofingStandardsCompliance.name: Fire Proofing Standards Compliance
FireProofingStandardsCompliance.Definition: Information about compliance with regard to fire proofing related standards.

LightningProtectionStandardsCompliance.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
LightningProtectionStandardsCompliance.name: Lightning Protection Standards Compliance
LightningProtectionStandardsCompliance.Definition: Information about compliance with regard to lightning protection related standards.

IfcDistributionElementType.Definition: The Ifc Distribution Element Type defines a list of commonly shared property set definitions of an element and an optional set of product representations. It is used to define an element specification (i.e. the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type).
IfcDistributionElementType.Name: Distribution Element Type

IfcElement.Definition: An element is a generalization of all components that make up a facility.Elements are physically existent objects, although they might be void elements, such as holes. Elements either remain permanently in the facility, or only temporarily, as formwork does. Elements can be either assembled on site or pre-manufactured and built in on site.
IfcElement.Name: Element

AtmosphericAcidificationPerUnit.name: Atmospheric Acidification Per Unit
AtmosphericAcidificationPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of gases responsible for the atmospheric acidification calculated in equivalent SO2

ClimateChangePerUnit.name: Climate Change Per Unit
ClimateChangePerUnit.Definition: Quantity of greenhouse gases emitted calculated in equivalent CO2

EutrophicationPerUnit.name: Eutrophication Per Unit
EutrophicationPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of eutrophicating compounds calculated in equivalent PO4

FunctionalUnitReference.name: Functional Unit Reference
FunctionalUnitReference.Definition: Reference to a database or a classification

IndicatorsUnit.name: Indicators Unit
IndicatorsUnit.Definition: The unit of the quantity the environmental indicators values are related with.

LifeCyclePhase.name: Life Cycle Phase
LifeCyclePhase.Definition: The whole life cycle or only a given phase from which environmental data are valid.

NonHazardousWastePerUnit.name: Non Hazardous Waste Per Unit
NonHazardousWastePerUnit.Definition: Quantity of non hazardous waste generated

NonRenewableEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.name: Non Renewable Energy Consumption Per Unit
NonRenewableEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of non-renewable energy used as defined in ISO219302007

PhotochemicalOzoneFormationPerUnit.name: Photochemical Ozone Formation Per Unit
PhotochemicalOzoneFormationPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of gases creating the photochemical ozone calculated in equivalent ethylene

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

RenewableEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.name: Renewable Energy Consumption Per Unit
RenewableEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of renewable energy used as defined in ISO219302007

ResourceDepletionPerUnit.name: Resource Depletion Per Unit
ResourceDepletionPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of resources used calculated in equivalent antimony

StratosphericOzoneLayerDestructionPerUni.name: Stratospheric Ozone Layer Destruction Per Unit
StratosphericOzoneLayerDestructionPerUni.Definition: Quantity of gases destroying the stratospheric ozone layer calculated in equivalent CFC-R11

TotalPrimaryEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.name: Total Primary Energy Consumption Per Unit
TotalPrimaryEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of energy used as defined in ISO219302007.

AtmosphericAcidification.name: Atmospheric Acidification
AtmosphericAcidification.Definition: Quantity of gases responsible for the atmospheric acidification calculated in equivalent SO2.

ClimateChange.name: Climate Change
ClimateChange.Definition: Quantity of greenhouse gases emitted calculated in equivalent CO2.

Eutrophication.name: Eutrophication
Eutrophication.Definition: Quantity of eutrophicating compounds calculated in equivalent PO4.

LeadInTime.name: Lead In Time
LeadInTime.Definition: Lead in time before start of process.

LeadOutTime.name: Lead Out Time
LeadOutTime.Definition: Lead out time after end of process.

NonHazardousWaste.name: Non Hazardous Waste
NonHazardousWaste.Definition: Quantity of non hazardous waste generated.

NonRenewableEnergyConsumption.name: Non Renewable Energy Consumption
NonRenewableEnergyConsumption.Definition: Quantity of non-renewable energy used as defined in ISO219302007

PhotochemicalOzoneFormation.name: Photochemical Ozone Formation
PhotochemicalOzoneFormation.Definition: Quantity of gases creating the photochemical ozone calculated in equivalent ethylene.

RenewableEnergyConsumption.name: Renewable Energy Consumption
RenewableEnergyConsumption.Definition: Quantity of renewable energy used as defined in ISO219302007

ResourceDepletion.name: Resource Depletion
ResourceDepletion.Definition: Quantity of resources used calculated in equivalent antimony.

StratosphericOzoneLayerDestruction.name: Stratospheric Ozone Layer Destruction
StratosphericOzoneLayerDestruction.Definition: Quantity of gases destroying the stratospheric ozone layer calculated in equivalent CFC-R11.

TotalPrimaryEnergyConsumption.name: Total Primary Energy Consumption
TotalPrimaryEnergyConsumption.Definition: Quantity of energy used as defined in ISO219302007.

MaximumAtmosphericPressure.name: Maximum Atmospheric Pressure
MaximumAtmosphericPressure.Definition: Maximum level of atmospheric pressure that the equipment can operate effectively in.

MaximumRainIntensity.name: Maximum Rain Intensity
MaximumRainIntensity.Definition: Maximum level of rain intensity that the equipment can operate effectively in. It is usually measured in millimeter per hour (mmh).

MaximumSolarRadiation.name: Maximum Solar Radiation
MaximumSolarRadiation.Definition: Maximum level of solar irradiance that the equipment can operate effectively in. This is usually tested and measured by a national or international standard. The value indicates power density measured in watt per square meter (wm2).

MaximumWindSpeed.name: Maximum Wind Speed
MaximumWindSpeed.Definition: Maximum resistance to wind load exposure.

OperationalTemperatureRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
OperationalTemperatureRange.name: Operational Temperature Range
OperationalTemperatureRange.Definition: The temperature range in which the device operates normally.

ReferenceAirRelativeHumidity.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
