ReferenceAirRelativeHumidity.name: Reference Air Relative Humidity
ReferenceAirRelativeHumidity.Definition: Measurement of the ratio of water vapor in the air.

ReferenceEnvironmentTemperature.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ReferenceEnvironmentTemperature.name: Reference Environment Temperature

SaltMistLevel.name: Salt Mist Level
SaltMistLevel.Definition: Maximum level of salt mist that the equipment can operate effectively in. It is provided according to an international or national standard.

SeismicResistance.name: Seismic Resistance
SeismicResistance.Definition: Maximum magnitude of earthquake that the equipment complies with. The value indicates earthquake intensity measured in Richter scale.

SmokeLevel.name: Smoke Level
SmokeLevel.Definition: Maximum level of smoke that the equipment complies with. It is provided according to an international or national standard.

StorageTemperatureRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
StorageTemperatureRange.name: Storage Temperature Range
StorageTemperatureRange.Definition: Allowed storage temperature range that the element complies with.

AcceptanceDate.name: Acceptance Date
AcceptanceDate.Definition: Date on which the element is accepted by the manager or administrator.

InstallationDate.name: Installation Date
InstallationDate.Definition: Date on which the element is installed.

PutIntoOperationDate.name: Put Into Operation Date
PutIntoOperationDate.Definition: Date on which the element is put into operation.

RepairContent.name: Repair Content
RepairContent.Definition: Content of repair, reason and nature can be given, e.g. display faults, communication failure, display exchange.

RepairDate.name: Repair Date
RepairDate.Definition: Date on which the last repair is done on the asset.

AssessmentCondition.name: Assessment Condition
AssessmentCondition.Definition: The overall condition of a product based on an assessment of the contributions to the overall condition made by the various criteria considered. The meanings given to the values of assessed condition should be agreed and documented by local agreements. For instance, is overall condition measured on a scale of 1 - 10 or by assigning names such as Good, OK, Poor.

AssessmentDate.name: Assessment Date
AssessmentDate.Definition: Date on which the overall condition is assessed

AssessmentFrequency.name: Assessment Frequency
AssessmentFrequency.Definition: Indicates how often the equipment should be assessed, to have a clear estimation on its working state, based on which the maintenance staff can decide whether it requires maintenance or requires to be updated or replaced.

AssessmentMethod.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AssessmentMethod.name: Assessment Method
AssessmentMethod.Definition: External reference to assessment method or application used to perform the assessment.

AssessmentType.name: Assessment Type
AssessmentType.Definition: Category of latest condition assessment report of the asset.

LastAssessmentReport.name: Last Assessment Report
LastAssessmentReport.Definition: Reference to latest condition (state of health) report.

ProcurementMethod.name: Procurement Method
ProcurementMethod.Definition: The method by which an Ifc Product TypeIfc Product is acquired and installed. The value provided shall be one of the following four character acronyms CFCI (meaning Contractor Furnished Contractor Installed), OFCI (meaning Owner Furnished Contractor Installed), or OFOI (meaning Owner Furnished Owner Installed).

SpecificationSectionNumber.name: Specification Section Number
SpecificationSectionNumber.Definition: A reference number to an external contract technical specification section describing either (a) minimum performance requirements of a given Ifc Product TypeIfc Product or (b) a preselection for a specific Ifc Product TypeIfc Product made for this project.

SubmittalIdentifer.name: Submittal Identifer
SubmittalIdentifer.Definition: The reference number to an external construction administration submittal used by the construction contractor andor subcontractor to verify that the referenced Ifc Product TypeIfc Product selection conforms with the requirements found in the referenced Specification Section Number.

AssetIdentifier.name: Asset Identifier
AssetIdentifier.Definition: A unique identification assigned to an asset that enables its differentiation from other assets.

InstallationDate.name: Installation Date
InstallationDate.Definition: Date on which the element is installed.

ModelNumber.name: Model Number
ModelNumber.Definition: The model number andor unit designator assigned by the manufacturer of the manufactured item.

AccidentResponse.name: Accident Response
AccidentResponse.Definition: Accident response chosen for the asset

AssetCriticality.name: Asset Criticality
AssetCriticality.Definition: Rating of the assets criticality to the operation of the facility

AssetFrailty.name: Asset Frailty
AssetFrailty.Definition: Rating of the assets frailty to breakage or deterioration

AssetPriority.name: Asset Priority
AssetPriority.Definition: Combined criticality and frailty rating indicating the operational and maintenance priority of the asset

MonitoringType.name: Monitoring Type
MonitoringType.Definition: Monitoring strategy chosen for the asset

ConditionDisposalLevel.name: Condition Disposal Level
ConditionDisposalLevel.Definition: Condition that will trigger a disposal process

ConditionReplacementLevel.name: Condition Replacement Level
ConditionReplacementLevel.Definition: Condition that will trigger a replacement process

DurationDisposalLevel.name: Duration Disposal Level
DurationDisposalLevel.Definition: Duration interval at which disposal is performed

DurationMaintenanceLevel.name: Duration Maintenance Level
DurationMaintenanceLevel.Definition: Duration interval at which maintenance is performed

DurationReplacementLevel.name: Duration Replacement Level
DurationReplacementLevel.Definition: Duration interval at which replacement is performed

DurationTargetPerformance.name: Duration Target Performance
DurationTargetPerformance.Definition: Target time to failure of the asset

DisposalLevel.name: Disposal Level
DisposalLevel.Definition: Performance level at which disposal takes place

PerformanceMaintenanceLevel.name: Performance Maintenance Level
PerformanceMaintenanceLevel.Definition: Performance level at which maintenance takes place

ReplacementLevel.name: Replacement Level
ReplacementLevel.Definition: Performance level at which replacement takes place

TargetPerformance.name: Target Performance
TargetPerformance.Definition: Target capacity or performance of the asset. Units of the performance value are specified through the property Value units attribute.

AcquisitionDate.name: Acquisition Date
AcquisitionDate.Definition: The date that the manufactured item was purchased.

AssemblyPlace.name: Assembly Place
AssemblyPlace.Definition: Enumeration defining where the assembly is intended to take place, either in a factory, other offsite location or on the building site.

BarCode.name: Bar Code
BarCode.Definition: The identity of the bar code given to an occurrence of the product.

BatchReference.name: Batch Reference
BatchReference.Definition: The identity of the batch reference from which an occurrence of a product is taken.

ManufacturingDate.name: Manufacturing Date
ManufacturingDate.Definition: Date on which the element was manufactured.

SerialNumber.name: Serial Number
SerialNumber.Definition: The manufacturers serial number assigned to an occurrence of a product.

ArticleNumber.name: Article Number
ArticleNumber.Definition: Article number or reference that is be applied to a configured product according to a standard scheme for article number definition as defined by the manufacturer. It is often used as the purchasing number.

AssemblyPlace.name: Assembly Place
AssemblyPlace.Definition: Enumeration defining where the assembly is intended to take place, either in a factory, other offsite location or on the building site.

GlobalTradeItemNumber.name: Global Trade Item Number
GlobalTradeItemNumber.Definition: The Global Trade Item Number (GTIN) is an identifier for trade items developed by GS1 (www.gs1.org).

Manufacturer.name: Manufacturer
Manufacturer.Definition: The organization that manufactured andor assembled the item.

ModelLabel.name: Model Label
ModelLabel.Definition: The descriptive model name of the product model (or product line) as assigned by the manufacturer of the manufactured item.

ModelReference.name: Model Reference
ModelReference.Definition: The model number or designator of the product model (or product line) as assigned by the manufacturer of the manufactured item.

OperationalDocument.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
OperationalDocument.name: Operational Document

PerformanceCertificate.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
PerformanceCertificate.name: Performance Certificate

ProductionYear.name: Production Year
ProductionYear.Definition: The year of production of the manufactured item.

SafetyDocument.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SafetyDocument.name: Safety Document

MeanTimeBetweenFailure.name: Mean Time Between Failure
MeanTimeBetweenFailure.Definition: The average time duration between instances of failure of a product.

ServiceLifeDuration.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ServiceLifeDuration.name: Service Life Duration
ServiceLifeDuration.Definition: The length or duration of a service life.The lower bound indicates pessimistic service life, the upper bound indicates optimistic service life, and the setpoint indicates the typical service life.

Exclusions.name: Exclusions
Exclusions.Definition: Items, conditions or actions that may be excluded from the warranty or that may cause the warranty to become void.

IsExtendedWarranty.name: Is Extended Warranty
IsExtendedWarranty.Definition: Indication of whether this is an extended warranty whose duration is greater than that normally assigned to an artefact (TRUE) or not ( FALSE).

PointOfContact.name: Point of Contact
PointOfContact.Definition: The organization that should be contacted for action under the terms of the warranty. Note that the role of the organization (manufacturer, supplier, installer etc.) is determined by the Ifc Actor Role attribute of Ifc Organization.

WarrantyIdentifier.name: Warranty Identifier
WarrantyIdentifier.Definition: The identifier assigned to a warranty.

WarrantyPeriod.name: Warranty Period
WarrantyPeriod.Definition: The time duration during which a manufacturer or supplier guarantees or warrants the performance of an artefact.

WarrantyStartDate.name: Warranty Start Date
WarrantyStartDate.Definition: The date on which the warranty commences.

CyclicPath.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
CyclicPath.name: Cyclic Path
CyclicPath.Definition: Represents the timeangle table of the kinematic behaviour.

CyclicRange.name: Cyclic Range
CyclicRange.Definition: Identifies the angular range of the kinematic behaviour

LinearPath.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
LinearPath.name: Linear Path
LinearPath.Definition: Represents the timedistance table of the kinematic behaviour.

LinearRange.name: Linear Range
LinearRange.Definition: Identifies the linear range of the kinematic behaviour.

MaximumAngularVelocity.name: Maximum Angular Velocity
MaximumAngularVelocity.Definition: Identifies the maximum angular velocity of the kinematic behaviour.

MaximumConstantSpeed.name: Maximum Constant Speed
MaximumConstantSpeed.Definition: Identifies the maximum constant speed over the kinematic path.

MinimumTime.name: Minimum Time
MinimumTime.Definition: Identifies the minimum time for the kinematic behaviour.

Tag.name: Tag
Tag.Definition: The tag (or label) identifier at the particular instance of a product, e.g. the serial number, or the position number. It is the identifier at the occurrence level.

ElementType.name: Element Type
ElementType.Definition: The type denotes a particular type that indicates the object further. The use has to be established at the level of instantiable subtypes. In particular it holds the user defined type, if the enumeration of the attribute Predefined Type is set to USERDEFINED.

IfcElementAssembly.Definition: The Ifc Element Assembly represents complex element assemblies aggregated from several elements, such as discrete elements, building elements, or other elements.
IfcElementAssembly.Name: Element Assembly

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: Status of the element, predominately used in renovation or retrofitting projects. The status can be assigned to as New - element designed as new addition, Existing - element exists and remains, Demolish - element existed but is to be demolished, Temporary - element will exists only temporary (like a temporary support structure).

AssemblyPlace.Definition: A designation of where the assembly is intended to take place defined by an Enum.

IfcElementAssemblyType.Definition: The Ifc Element Assembly Type defines a list of commonly shared property set definitions of an element and an optional set of product representations. It is used to define an element specification (i.e. the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type).
IfcElementAssemblyType.Name: Element Assembly Type

IfcElementQuantity.Definition: An Ifc Element Quantity defines a set of derived measures of an elements physical property. Elements could be spatial structure elements (like buildings, storeys, or spaces) or building elements (like walls, slabs, finishes). The Ifc Element Quantity gets assigned to the element by using the Ifc Rel Defines By Properties relationship.The optional Method Of Measurement attribute defines the code, e.g. from a standard method of measurement, which had been used to calculate the element quantity.
IfcElementQuantity.Name: Element Quantity

MethodOfMeasurement.name: Method of Measurement
MethodOfMeasurement.Definition: Name of the method of measurement used to calculate the element quantity. The method of measurement attribute has to be made recognizable by further agreements. IFC2x2-Addendum-1 change The attribute has been changed to be optional

IfcElementType.Definition: Ifc Element Type defines a list of commonly shared property set definitions of an element and an optional set of product representations. It is used to define an element specification (i.e. the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type).
IfcElementType.Name: Element Type

IfcExternalSpatialElement.Definition: The external spatial element defines external regions at the building site. Those regions can be definedlogically - for example, an instance of Ifc External Spatial Element could represent the air space around the building without having an own shape representation, or
IfcExternalSpatialElement.Name: External Spatial Element

IfcExternalSpatialStructureElement.Definition: The external spatial structure element is an abstract entity provided for different kind of external spaces, regions, and volumes.
IfcExternalSpatialStructureElement.Name: External Spatial Structure Element

IfcFacility.Definition: A Facility (derived from Ifc Spatial Structure Element) may be an Ifc Building, an Ifc Bridge, an Ifc Railway, an Ifc Road, an Ifc Marine Facility (or any other type of built facility defined in the future, such as Ifc Tunnel).
IfcFacility.Name: Facility

IfcFacilityPart.Definition: Ifc Facility Part provides for spatial breakdown of built facilities. It may be further specialised according to the type of facility being broken down.
IfcFacilityPart.Name: Facility Part

Width.name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

UsageType.Definition: Defines the convention used to subdivide or decompose the facility.

IfcFacilityPartCommon.Definition: A part that is not clearly part of one domain but is a hybrid and has shared responsibilities in multiple domains.For example Level crossing, junctions, etc.
IfcFacilityPartCommon.Name: Facility Part Common

IfcFeatureElement.Definition: A feature element is a generalization of all existence dependent elements which modify the shape and appearance of the associated master element. The Ifc Feature Element offers the ability to handle shape modifiers as semantic objects within the IFC object model.
IfcFeatureElement.Name: Feature Element

IfcFeatureElementAddition.Definition: A feature element addition is a specialization of the general feature element, that represents an existence dependent element which modifies the shape and appearance of the associated master element. The Ifc Feature Element Addition offers the ability to handle shape modifiers as semantic objects within the IFC object model that add to the shape of the master element.The Ifc Feature Element Addition is associated to its master element by virtue of the objectified relationship Ifc Rel Projects Element. This relationship implies a Boolean union operation between the shape of the master element and the shape of the addition feature.The local placement for Ifc Feature Element Addition is defined in its supertype Ifc Product. It is defined by the Ifc Local Placement, which defines the local coordinate system that is referenced by all geometric representations. The local placement is always defined in relation to the local placement of the element to which the feature element is addedThe Placement Rel To attribute of Ifc Object Placement shall point (if given) to the object placement of the Ifc Element, which is used in the Projects Elements.Relating Element inverse attribute (the parent element of the feature).
IfcFeatureElementAddition.Name: Feature Element Addition

IfcFeatureElementSubtraction.Definition: The Ifc Feature Element Subtraction is specialization of the general feature element, that represents an existence dependent element which modifies the shape and appearance of the associated master element. The Ifc Feature Element Subtraction offers the ability to handle shape modifiers as semantic objects within the IFC object model that subtract from the shape of the master element.
IfcFeatureElementSubtraction.Name: Feature Element Subtraction

IfcFurnishingElement.Definition: A furnishing element is a generalization of all furniture related objects. Furnishing objects are characterized as beingpre-manufactured and assembled on-site, or
IfcFurnishingElement.Name: Furnishing Element

IfcFurnishingElementType.Definition: Ifc Furnishing Element Type defines a list of commonly shared property set definitions of an element and an optional set of product representations. It is used to define an element specification (the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type).
IfcFurnishingElementType.Name: Furnishing Element Type

IfcGeographicElement.Definition: An Ifc Geographic Element is a generalization of all elements within a geographical landscape. It includes occurrences of typical geographical elements, often referred to as features, such as trees or terrain. Common type information behind several occurrences of Ifc Geographic Element is provided by the Ifc Geographic Element Type.
IfcGeographicElement.Name: Geographic Element

IfcGeographicElementType.Definition: An Ifc Geographic Element Type is used to define an element specification of a geographic element (i.e. the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type). Geographic element types include for different types of element that may be used to represent information within a geographical landscape external to a building. Within the world of geographic information they are referred to generally as features. Ifc Geographic Element Types includepoint features such as seating, bus shelters, signage, trees
IfcGeographicElementType.Name: Geographic Element Type

IfcGrid.Definition: Ifc Grid ia a planar design grid defined in 3D space used as an aid in locating structural and design elements. The position of the grid (Object Placement) is defined by a 3D coordinate system (and thereby the design grid can be used in plan, section or in any position relative to the world coordinate system). The position can be relative to the object placement of other products or grids. The XY plane of the 3D coordinate system is used to place the grid axes, which are 2D curves (for example, line, circle, arc, polyline).The inherited attributes Name and Description can be used to define a descriptive name of the grid and to indicate the grids purpose. A grid is defined by (normally) two, or (in case of a triangular grid) three lists of grid axes. The following figures show some examples.A grid may support a rectangular layout as shown in Figure 1, a radial layout as shown in Figure 2, or a triangular layout as shown in Figure 3.
IfcGrid.Name: Grid

IfcImpactProtectionDevice.Definition: An impact protection device is a component used to protect other built elements from kinetic damage. Impact protection devices currently come in different varietiesA vibration damper used to minimize the effects of vibration in a structure by dissipating kinetic energy. The damper may be passive (elastic, frictional, inertia) or active (in a system using sensors and actuators).
IfcImpactProtectionDevice.Name: Impact Protection Device

IfcImpactProtectionDeviceType.Definition: The Ifc Impact Protection Device Type provides the type information for Ifc Impact Protection Device occurrences.
IfcImpactProtectionDeviceType.Name: Impact Protection Device Type

IfcLinearElement.Definition: A generalization of all linear elements that are parts of an alignment.
IfcLinearElement.Name: Linear Element

IfcLinearPositioningElement.Definition: An Ifc Linear Positioning Element is an entity describing positioning according to a curve.
IfcLinearPositioningElement.Name: Linear Positioning Element

IfcOpeningElement.Definition: The opening element stands for opening, recess or chase, all reflecting voids. It represents a void within any element that has physical manifestation. Openings can be inserted into walls, slabs, beams, columns, or other elements.There are two different types of opening elements. The attribute Predefined Type should be used to capture the differencesan opening, where the thickness of the opening is greater or equal to the thickness of the element —
IfcOpeningElement.Name: Opening Element

FireExit.name: Fire Exit
FireExit.Definition: Indication whether this object is designed to serve as an exit in the case of fire (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

FireRating.name: Fire Rating
FireRating.Definition: Fire rating for this object. It is given according to the national fire safety classification.

Purpose.name: Purpose
Purpose.Definition: Indication of the purpose of this object

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: Status of the element, predominately used in renovation or retrofitting projects. The status can be assigned to as New - element designed as new addition, Existing - element exists and remains, Demolish - element existed but is to be demolished, Temporary - element will exists only temporary (like a temporary support structure).

Width.name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcPort.Definition: A port provides the means for an element to connect to other elements.An Ifc Port is associated with an Ifc Element it belongs to through the objectified relationship Ifc Rel Nests if such port is fixed, or Ifc Rel Connects Port To Element if such port is dynamically attached. Exactly two ports, belonging to two different elements, are connected with each other through the objectified relationship Ifc Rel Connects Ports.An instance of Ifc Element may have one or more points at which it connects to other instances of Ifc Element. An instance of Ifc Port is located at a point where a connection can occur. The location of the port is determined in the context of the local coordinate system of the element to which it belongs. As a subordinate part being fully dependent on the master element the Ifc Port shall have no independent containment relationship to the spatial structure.The local placement for Ifc Port is defined in its supertype Ifc Product. It is defined by the Ifc Local Placement, which defines the local coordinate system that is referenced by all geometric representations. The Placement Rel To relationship of Ifc Local Placement shall point to the local placement of the master Ifc Element or Ifc Element Type (relevant subtypes), which is related to the Ifc Port by the relationship object Ifc Rel Nests for fixed ports, or Ifc Rel Connects Port To Element for dynamic ports.
IfcPort.Name: Port

IfcPositioningElement.Definition: New and abstract entity definition for positioning and annotating elements that are used to position other elements relatively.
IfcPositioningElement.Name: Positioning Element

IfcProjectionElement.Definition: The projection element is a specialization of the general feature element to represent projections applied to building elements. It represents a solid attached to any element that has physical manifestation.
IfcProjectionElement.Name: Projection Element

IfcReferent.Definition: Ifc Referent defines a position at a particular offset along an alignment curve.Referents may be used for several scenariospositioning physical elements at common locations along an alignment curve (e.g. bridge piers)
IfcReferent.Name: Referent

LRMConstraint.name: Lrmconstraint
LRMConstraint.Definition: Allows for the specification of constraints imposed by this Linear Referencing Method. For example, a Reference Post Linear Referencing Method may specify that referents be of type reference marker.

LRMName.name: Lrmname
LRMName.Definition: Gives the name of this Linear Referencing Method, such as kilometre-point.

LRMType.name: Lrmtype
LRMType.Definition: Gives the type of this Linear Referencing Method.

LRMUnit.name: Lrmunit
LRMUnit.Definition: Specifies the units of measure used by this Linear Referencing Method for measures along the linear element being measured.

UserDefinedLRMType.name: User Defined Lrmtype
UserDefinedLRMType.Definition: Gives the user defined type of this Linear Referencing Method when property LRMType is LRMUSERDEFINED.

NameFormat.name: Name Format
NameFormat.Definition: Specifies a reference to or description of the formatting or encoding of the Name attribute of the Ifc Referent occurrence.

HasIncreasingStation.name: Has Increasing Station
HasIncreasingStation.Definition: Inform on the increasing or decreasing progress of stationing values, for referents nested in a given alignment.If present and true, or if not present, then the relevant subsequently nested referents are expected to have greater PsetStationing.Station values (i.e., increasing stations).If present and false, then the relevant subsequently nested referents are expected to have lower PsetStationing.Station values (i.e., decreasing stations).

IncomingStation.name: Incoming Station
IncomingStation.Definition: The optional station value of the incoming segment that ends at this location. This value needs to be set if the intention is to specify a station equation, i.e. a location where stationing changes.

Station.name: Station
Station.Definition: The station value at this location.

IfcRelAdheresToElement.Definition: The Ifc Rel Adheres To Element is an objectified relationship between an element and one to many surface feature elements that adhere to the surface of the element. The relationship is defined to be a 1 to many relationship. The Ifc Rel Adheres To Element establishes an aggregation relationship between the main element and a sub ordinary surface feature.
IfcRelAdheresToElement.Name: Rel Adheres to Element

IfcRelAssociatesMaterial.Definition: Ifc Rel Associates Material is an objectified relationship between a material definition and elements or element types to which this material definition applies.The material definition can beassigned to an element occurrence as a specific usage of a layer set or profile set
IfcRelAssociatesMaterial.Name: Rel Associates Material

IfcRelAssociatesProfileDef.Definition: Associates Objects with a profile definition.
IfcRelAssociatesProfileDef.Name: Rel Associates Profile Def

IfcRelConnectsElements.Definition: The Ifc Rel Connects Elements objectified relationship provides the generalization of the connectivity between elements. It is a 1 to 1 relationship. The concept of two elements being physically or logically connected is described independently from the connecting elements. The connectivity may be related to the shape representation of the connected entities by providing a connection geometry.In this case the geometrical constraints of the connection are provided by the optional relationship to the Ifc Connection Geometry. The connection geometry is provided as a point, curve or surface within the local placement coordinate systems of the connecting elements.
IfcRelConnectsElements.Name: Rel Connects Elements

IfcRelConnectsPorts.Definition: An Ifc Rel Connects Ports relationship defines the relationship that is made between two ports at their point of connection. It may include the connection geometry between two ports.The objectified relationship Ifc Rel Connects Ports is required for defining how two instances of Ifc Port connect together. Each of the ports is logically contained within the Ifc Distribution Element by using the ordered collection Ifc Rel Nests.
IfcRelConnectsPorts.Name: Rel Connects Ports

IfcRelConnectsPortToElement.Definition: Ifc Rel Connects Port To Element is a relationship between a distribution element and dynamically connected ports where connections are realised to other distribution elements.Ports contained in different elements are connected to each other using the Ifc Rel Connects Ports relationship.
IfcRelConnectsPortToElement.Name: Rel Connects Port to Element

IfcRelConnectsWithRealizingElements.Definition: Ifc Rel Connects With Realizing Elements defines a generic relationship that is made between two elements that require the realization of that relationship by means of further realizing elements.An Ifc Rel Connects With Realizing Elements is a specialization of Ifc Rel Connects Elements where the connecting operation has the additional attribute of (one or many) realizing elements that may be used to realize or further qualify the relationship. It is defined as a ternary relationship.
IfcRelConnectsWithRealizingElements.Name: Rel Connects With Realizing Elements

ConnectionType.name: Connection Type
ConnectionType.Definition: The type of the connection given for informal purposes, it may include labels, like joint, rigid joint, flexible joint, etc.

IfcRelContainedInSpatialStructure.Definition: This objectified relationship, Ifc Rel Contained In Spatial Structure, is used to assign elements to a certain level of the spatial project structure. Any element can only be assigned once to a certain level of the spatial structure. The question, which level is relevant for which type of element, can only be answered within the context of a particular project and might vary within the various regions.
IfcRelContainedInSpatialStructure.Name: Rel Contained In Spatial Structure

IfcRelFillsElement.Definition: Ifc Rel Fills Element is an objectified relationship between an opening element and an element that fills (or partially fills) the opening element. It is an one-to-one relationship.
IfcRelFillsElement.Name: Rel Fills Element

IfcRelInterferesElements.Definition: The Ifc Rel Interferes Elements objectified relationship indicates that two elements interfere.
IfcRelInterferesElements.Name: Rel Interferes Elements

ImpliedOrder.name: Implied Order
ImpliedOrder.Definition: Logical value indicating if the Relating Element is considered a source and the Related Element a target (giving a formal orientation to the relation). It shall be provided in regards to Interference Geometry usage and Interference Type declaration.

InterferenceType.name: Interference Type
InterferenceType.Definition: Optional identifier that describes the nature of the interference.

IfcRelPositions.Definition: An Ifc Rel Positions relationship informs on the positioning dependency between a product and a positioning element.This relationship does not affect the geometric representation of a product nor its geometrical placement, which is done through subtypes of Ifc Object Placement.
IfcRelPositions.Name: Rel Positions

IfcRelProjectsElement.Definition: The Ifc Rel Projects Element is an objectified relationship between an element and one projection element that creates a modifier to the shape of the element. The relationship is defined to be a 11 relationship, if an element has more than one projection, several relationship objects have to be used, each pointing to a different projection element. The Ifc Rel Projects Element establishes an aggregation relationship between the main element and a sub ordinary addition feature.
IfcRelProjectsElement.Name: Rel Projects Element

IfcRelReferencedInSpatialStructure.Definition: The objectified relationship, Ifc Rel Referenced In Spatial Structure is used to assign elements in addition to those levels of the project spatial structure, in which they are referenced, but not primarily contained. It is also used to connect a system to the relevant spatial element that it serves.
IfcRelReferencedInSpatialStructure.Name: Rel Referenced In Spatial Structure

IfcRelServicesBuildings.Definition: The Ifc Rel Services Buildings is an objectified relationship that defines the relationship between a system and the sites, buildings, storeys, spaces, or spatial zones, it serves. Examples of systems arebuilding service systems (heating, cooling, waste water system) represented by instances of Ifc Distribution System
IfcRelServicesBuildings.Name: Rel Services Buildings

IfcRelSpaceBoundary.Definition: The space boundary defines the physical or virtual delimiter of a space by the relationship Ifc Rel Space Boundary to the surrounding elements.In the case of a physical space boundary, the placement and shape of the boundary may be given, and the building element, providing the boundary is referenced,
IfcRelSpaceBoundary.Name: Rel Space Boundary

InternalOrExternalBoundary.Definition: Defines whether the Space Boundary is INTERNAL, or EXTERNAL, i.e. adjacent to open space that can be a partially enclosed space, such as terrace.

PhysicalOrVirtualBoundary.Definition: Defines whether the Space Boundary is PHYISICAL or VIRTUAL.

IfcRelSpaceBoundary1stLevel.Definition: The 1st level space boundary defines the physical or virtual delimiter of a space by the relationship Ifc Rel Space Boundary1st Level to the surrounding elements. 1st level space boundaries are characterized by1st level space boundaries are the boundaries of a space defined by the surfaces of building elements bounding this space (physical space boundaries) or by virtual surfaces provided by an adjacent space with no dividing wall.
IfcRelSpaceBoundary1stLevel.Name: Rel Space Boundary1St Level

IfcRelSpaceBoundary2ndLevel.Definition: The 2nd level space boundary defines the physical or virtual delimiter of a space by the relationship Ifc Rel Space Boundary2nd Level to the surrounding elements. 2nd level space boundaries are characterized by2nd level space boundaries still represent building elements that bound the space, but are more granular in that they are subdivided in any of the following cases
IfcRelSpaceBoundary2ndLevel.Name: Rel Space Boundary2Nd Level

IfcRelVoidsElement.Definition: Ifc Rel Voids Element is an objectified relationship between a building element and one opening element that creates a void in the element. It is a one-to-one relationship. This relationship implies a boolean operation of subtraction between the geometric bodies of the element and the opening.As shown in Figure 1, the insertion of a void into a wall is represented by the relationship Ifc Rel Voids Element. The opening within the wall is defined by the pattern Ifc Wall - Ifc Rel Voids Element - Ifc Opening Element.Figure 1 — Relationship for element voiding
IfcRelVoidsElement.Name: Rel Voids Element

IfcSite.Definition: A site is a defined area of land, possibly covered with water, on which the project construction is to be completed. A site may be used to erect, retrofit or turn down building(s), or for other construction related developments.
IfcSite.Name: Site

AddressLines.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AddressLines.name: Address Lines

Country.name: Country
Country.Definition: The two letter country code (from ISO 3166).

ElectronicMailAddresses.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ElectronicMailAddresses.name: Electronic Mail Addresses
ElectronicMailAddresses.Definition: The list of Email addresses at which Email messages may be received.

FacsimileNumbers.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
FacsimileNumbers.name: Facsimile Numbers
FacsimileNumbers.Definition: The list of fax numbers at which fax messages may be received.

InternalLocation.name: Internal Location
InternalLocation.Definition: An organization defined address for internal mail delivery.

MessagingIDs.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
MessagingIDs.name: Messaging Ids
MessagingIDs.Definition: IDs or addresses for any other means of telecommunication, for example instant messaging, voice-over-IP, or file transfer protocols. The communication protocol is indicated by the URI value with scheme designations such as irc, sip, or ftp.

PagerNumber.name: Pager Number
PagerNumber.Definition: The pager number at which paging messages may be received.

PostalBox.name: Postal Box
PostalBox.Definition: An address that is implied by an identifiable mail drop.

PostalCode.name: Postal Code
PostalCode.Definition: The code that is used by the countrys postal service.

Purpose.name: Purpose
Purpose.Definition: Indication of the purpose of this object

TelephoneNumbers.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TelephoneNumbers.name: Telephone Numbers
TelephoneNumbers.Definition: The list of telephone numbers at which telephone messages may be received.

UserDefinedPurpose.name: User Defined Purpose
UserDefinedPurpose.Definition: Allows for specification of user specific purpose of the address beyond the enumeration values provided by Purpose attribute of type Ifc Address Type Enum. When a value is provided for attribute User Defined Purpose, in parallel the attribute Purpose shall have enumeration value USERDEFINED.

WWWHomePageURL.name: Wwwhome Page Url
WWWHomePageURL.Definition: The world wide web address at which the preliminary page of information for the person or organization can be located.

MaxAmbientTemp.name: Max Ambient Temp
MaxAmbientTemp.Definition: Maximum ambient temperature of the site used as a basis of design

MinAmbientTemp.name: Min Ambient Temp
MinAmbientTemp.Definition: Minimum ambient temperature of the site used as a basis of design

IsPermanentID.name: Is Permanent Id
IsPermanentID.Definition: Indicates whether the identity assigned to the object is permanent ( TRUE) or temporary (FALSE).

LandID.name: Land Id
LandID.Definition: Identification number assigned by the statutory registration authority to a land parcel.

LandTitleID.name: Land Title Id
LandTitleID.Definition: Identification number assigned by the statutory registration authority to the title to a land parcel.

BuildableArea.name: Buildable Area
BuildableArea.Definition: The area of site utilization expressed as a maximum value according to local building codes.

BuildingHeightLimit.name: Building Height Limit
BuildingHeightLimit.Definition: Allowed maximum height of buildings on this site - according to local building codes.

FloorAreaRatio.name: Floor Area Ratio
FloorAreaRatio.Definition: The ratio of all floor areas to the buildable area as the maximum floor area utilization of the site as a maximum value according to local building codes.

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

SiteCoverageRatio.name: Site Coverage Ratio
SiteCoverageRatio.Definition: The ratio of the utilization, Total Area Buildable Area, expressed as a maximum value. The ratio value may be used to derive Buildable Area.

TotalArea.name: Total Area
TotalArea.Definition: Total planned area for the site. Used for programming the site space.

GrossArea.name: Gross Area
GrossArea.Definition: Gross Area of the object. Openings, recesses, projections and cut-outs are not taken into account.

GrossPerimeter.name: Gross Perimeter
GrossPerimeter.Definition: Gross perimeter at the outer contour of the object.

LandTitleNumber.name: Land Title Number
LandTitleNumber.Definition: The land title number (designation of the site within a regional system).IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION This attribute shall not be used for export, use property Land Title ID at PsetLand Registration instead.

RefElevation.name: Ref Elevation
RefElevation.Definition: Datum elevation relative to sea level.

IfcSpace.Definition: A space represents an area or volume bounded actually or theoretically. Spaces are areas or volumes that provide for certain functions within a building.A space is associated to a building storey (or in case of exterior spaces to a site). A space may span over several connected spaces. Therefore a space group provides for a collection of spaces included in a storey. A space can also be decomposed in parts, where each part defines a partial space. This is defined by the Composition Type attribute of the supertype Ifc Spatial Structure Element which is interpreted as followCOMPLEX space group
IfcSpace.Name: Space

DownstreamConnections.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
DownstreamConnections.name: Downstream Connections
DownstreamConnections.Definition: Names of downstream connected equipment and spaces, if not otherwise represented

ProcessCapacity.name: Process Capacity
ProcessCapacity.Definition: The number of units that can be processed in the time defined in Process Performance

ProcessItem.name: Process Item
ProcessItem.Definition: The type of item (and its measurement method) being modelled within a process. This can be cargo, passengers or vehicles that pass through the system.

ProcessPerformance.name: Process Performance
ProcessPerformance.Definition: Minimum time to accept or dispatch the entire item capacity.

UpstreamConnections.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
UpstreamConnections.name: Upstream Connections
UpstreamConnections.Definition: Names of upstream connected equipment and spaces, if not otherwise represented

FinishCeilingHeight.name: Finish Ceiling Height
FinishCeilingHeight.Definition: Height of the suspended ceiling (from top of flooring to the bottom of the suspended ceiling). To be provided only if the space has a suspended ceiling with constant height.

FinishFloorHeight.name: Finish Floor Height
FinishFloorHeight.Definition: Height of the flooring (from base slab without flooring to the flooring height). To be provided only if the space has a constant flooring height.

GrossCeilingArea.name: Gross Ceiling Area
GrossCeilingArea.Definition: Sum of all ceiling areas of the space. It includes the area covered by elementsinside the space (columns, inner walls, etc.). The ceiling area is the real (and not the projected) area (e.g. in case of sloped ceilings).

GrossFloorArea.name: Gross Floor Area
GrossFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all gross floor areas within the spatial structure element.

GrossPerimeter.name: Gross Perimeter
GrossPerimeter.Definition: Gross perimeter at the outer contour of the object.

GrossVolume.name: Gross Volume
GrossVolume.Definition: Total gross volume of the object. Openings, recesses, enclosed objects and projections are not taken into account.

GrossWallArea.name: Gross Wall Area
GrossWallArea.Definition: Sum of all wall (and other vertically bounding elements, like columns) areas bounded by the space. It includes the area covered by elements inside the wall area (doors, windows, other openings, etc.).

NetCeilingArea.name: Net Ceiling Area
NetCeilingArea.Definition: Sum of all ceiling areas of the space. It excludes the area covered by elementsinside the space (columns, inner walls, etc.). The ceiling area is the real (and not the projected) area (e.g. in case of sloped ceilings).

NetFloorArea.name: Net Floor Area
NetFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all net usable floor areas.

NetPerimeter.name: Net Perimeter
NetPerimeter.Definition: Net perimeter at the floor level of this space. It excludes those parts of the perimeter that are created by by virtual boundaries and openings (like doors). It is the measurement used for skirting boards and may include the perimeter of internal fixed objects like columns.

NetVolume.name: Net Volume
NetVolume.Definition: Total net volume of the object, taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

NetWallArea.name: Net Wall Area
NetWallArea.Definition: Sum of all wall (and other vertically bounding elements, like columns) areas bounded by the space. It excludes the area covered by elements inside the wall area (doors, windows, other openings, etc.).

ElevationWithFlooring.name: Elevation With Flooring
ElevationWithFlooring.Definition: Level of flooring of this space the average shall be taken, if the space ground surface is sloping or if there are level differences within this space.

LongName.name: Long Name
LongName.Definition: Long name for a space type, used for informal purposes. It should be used, if available, in conjunction with the inherited Name attribute.

IfcSpaceType.Definition: A space represents an area or volume bounded actually or theoretically. Spaces are areas or volumes that provide for certain functions within a building.The Ifc Space Type defines a list of commonly shared information for occurrences of spaces. The set of shared information may includecommon properties within shared property sets
IfcSpaceType.Name: Space Type

IfcSpatialElement.Definition: A spatial element is the generalization of all spatial elements that might be used to define a spatial structure or to define spatial zones.a hierarchical spatial structure element as Ifc Spatial Structure Element
IfcSpatialElement.Name: Spatial Element

CoolingAirFlowRate.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
CoolingAirFlowRate.name: Cooling Air Flow Rate
CoolingAirFlowRate.Definition: Cooling air flow rate in the space.

ExhaustAirFlowRate.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ExhaustAirFlowRate.name: Exhaust Air Flow Rate
ExhaustAirFlowRate.Definition: Design exhaust air flow rate for the space.

HeatingAirFlowRate.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
HeatingAirFlowRate.name: Heating Air Flow Rate
HeatingAirFlowRate.Definition: Heating air flow rate in the space.

SpaceRelativeHumidity.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SpaceRelativeHumidity.name: Space Relative Humidity
SpaceRelativeHumidity.Definition: The relative humidity of the space.

SpaceTemperatureHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SpaceTemperatureHistory.name: Space Temperature History

VentilationAirFlowRateHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
VentilationAirFlowRateHistory.name: Ventilation Air Flow Rate History
VentilationAirFlowRateHistory.Definition: Ventilation air flow rate in the space.

GrossPlannedArea.name: Gross Planned Area
GrossPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned gross area of the spatial structure element. Used for programming the spatial structure element.

HandicapAccessible.name: Handicap Accessible
HandicapAccessible.Definition: Indication that this object is designed to be accessible by the handicapped. Set to (TRUE) if this object is rated as handicap accessible according to the local building codes, otherwise (FALSE). It is giving according to the requirements of the national building code.

IsExternal.name: Is External
IsExternal.Definition: Indication whether the element is designed for use in the exterior (TRUE) or not (FALSE). If (TRUE) it is an external element and faces the outside of the building.

NetPlannedArea.name: Net Planned Area
NetPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned net area of the object. Used for programming the object.

PubliclyAccessible.name: Publicly Accessible
PubliclyAccessible.Definition: Indication whether this space (in case of e.g., a toilet) is designed to serve as a publicly accessible space, e.g., for a public toilet (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

CeilingCovering.name: Ceiling Covering
CeilingCovering.Definition: Label to indicate the material or finish of the space ceiling. The label is used for room book information and often displayed in room stamp.The material information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeCEILING) object with own shape representation and material assignment. In case of inconsistency the material assigned to Ifc Covering elements takes precedence.

CeilingCoveringThickness.name: Ceiling Covering Thickness
CeilingCoveringThickness.Definition: Thickness of the material layer(s) for the space ceiling.The thickness information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeCEILING) object with own shape representation. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters of an assigned Ifc Covering and this attached property, the geometric parameters take precedence.

ConcealedCeiling.name: Concealed Ceiling
ConcealedCeiling.Definition: Indication whether this space is designed to have a concealed flooring space (TRUE) or not (FALSE). A concealed ceiling space is normally meant to be the space between a slab and a ceiling.

ConcealedCeilingOffset.name: Concealed Ceiling Offset
ConcealedCeilingOffset.Definition: Distance between the upper floor slab and the suspended ceiling, often used for distribution systems. Often referred to as plenum.

ConcealedFlooring.name: Concealed Flooring
ConcealedFlooring.Definition: Indication whether this space is designed to have a concealed flooring space (TRUE) or not (FALSE). A concealed flooring space is normally meant to be the space beneath a raised floor.

ConcealedFlooringOffset.name: Concealed Flooring Offset
ConcealedFlooringOffset.Definition: Distance between the floor slab and the floor covering, often used for cables and other installations. Often referred to as raised flooring.

FloorCovering.name: Floor Covering
FloorCovering.Definition: Label to indicate the material or finish of the space flooring. The label is used for room book information and often displayed in room stamp.The material information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeFLOORING) object with own shape representation and material assignment. In case of inconsistency the material assigned to Ifc Covering elements takes precedence.

FloorCoveringThickness.name: Floor Covering Thickness
FloorCoveringThickness.Definition: Thickness of the material layer(s) for the space flooring.The thickness information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeFLOORING) object with own shape representation. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters of an assigned Ifc Covering and this attached property, the geometric parameters take precedence.

Molding.name: Molding
Molding.Definition: Label to indicate the material or construction of the molding around the space ceiling. The label is used for room book information.The material information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeMOLDING) object with own shape representation and material assignment. In case of inconsistency the material assigned to Ifc Covering elements takes precedence.

MoldingHeight.name: Molding Height
MoldingHeight.Definition: Height of the molding.The height information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeMOLDING) object with own shape representation and material assignment. In case of inconsistency the height assigned to Ifc Covering elements takes precedence.

SkirtingBoard.name: Skirting Board
SkirtingBoard.Definition: Label to indicate the material or construction of the skirting board around the space flooring. The label is used for room book information.The material information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeSKIRTINGBOARD) object with own shape representation and material assignment. In case of inconsistency the material assigned to Ifc Covering elements takes precedence.

SkirtingBoardHeight.name: Skirting Board Height
SkirtingBoardHeight.Definition: Height of the skirting board.The height information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeSKIRTINGBOARD) object with own shape representation and material assignment. In case of inconsistency the height assigned to Ifc Covering elements takes precedence.

WallCovering.name: Wall Covering
WallCovering.Definition: Label to indicate the material or finish of the space cladding. The label is used for room book information and often displayed in room stamp.The material information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeCLADDING) object with own shape representation and material assignment. In case of inconsistency the material assigned to Ifc Covering elements takes precedence.

WallCoveringThickness.name: Wall Covering Thickness
WallCoveringThickness.Definition: Thickness of the material layer(s) for the space cladding.The thickness information is provided in absence of an Ifc Covering (typeCLADDING) object with own shape representation. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters of an assigned Ifc Covering and this attached property, the geometric parameters take precedence.

AirPressurization.name: Air Pressurization
AirPressurization.Definition: Indication whether the space is required to have pressurized air (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

FireExit.name: Fire Exit
FireExit.Definition: Indication whether this object is designed to serve as an exit in the case of fire (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

FireRiskFactor.name: Fire Risk Factor
FireRiskFactor.Definition: Fire Risk factor assigned to the space according to local building regulations. It defines the fire risk of the space at several levels of fire hazard.

FlammableStorage.name: Flammable Storage
FlammableStorage.Definition: Indication whether the space is intended to serve as a storage of flammable material (which is regarded as such by the presiding building code. (TRUE) indicates yes, (FALSE) otherwise.

SprinklerProtection.name: Sprinkler Protection
SprinklerProtection.Definition: Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.name: Sprinkler Protection Automatic
SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.Definition: Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

AirConditioning.name: Air Conditioning
AirConditioning.Definition: Indication whether this space requires air conditioning provided (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

AirConditioningCentral.name: Air Conditioning Central
AirConditioningCentral.Definition: Indication whether the space requires a central air conditioning provided (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

AirHandlingName.name: Air Handling Name
AirHandlingName.Definition: The name of the air side system.Ifc Rel Services Buildings should be used to reference the correct Air Handling System (Ifc System)

DiscontinuedHeating.name: Discontinued Heating
DiscontinuedHeating.Definition: Indication whether discontinued heating is requireddesirable from userdesigner view point. (TRUE) if yes, (FALSE) otherwise.

HumidityMax.name: Humidity Max
HumidityMax.Definition: Maximal permitted humidity of the space or zone that is required from userdesigner view point. If no summer or winter space humidity requirements are given, it applies all year, otherwise for the intermediate period.

HumidityMin.name: Humidity Min
HumidityMin.Definition: Minimal permitted humidity of the space or zone that is required from userdesigner view point. If no summer or winter space humidity requirements are given, it applies all year, otherwise for the intermediate period.

HumiditySetPoint.name: Humidity Set Point
HumiditySetPoint.Definition: Humidity of the space or zone that is required from userdesigner view point. If no summer or winter space humidity requirements are given, it applies all year, otherwise for the intermediate period. Provide this property, if no humidity range (Min-Max) is available.

HumiditySummer.name: Humidity Summer
HumiditySummer.Definition: Humidity of the space or zone for the hot (summer) period, that is required from userdesigner view point and provided as requirement for cooling.

HumidityWinter.name: Humidity Winter
HumidityWinter.Definition: Humidity of the space or zone for the cold (winter) period that is required from userdesigner view point and provided as requirement for heating.

MechanicalVentilation.name: Mechanical Ventilation
MechanicalVentilation.Definition: Indication whether the space is required to have mechanical ventilation (TRUE), or not (FALSE).

MechanicalVentilationRate.name: Mechanical Ventilation Rate
MechanicalVentilationRate.Definition: Indication of the requirement of a particular mechanical air ventilation rate, given in air changes per hour.

NaturalVentilation.name: Natural Ventilation
NaturalVentilation.Definition: Indication whether the space is required to have natural ventilation (TRUE), or not (FALSE).

NaturalVentilationRate.name: Natural Ventilation Rate
NaturalVentilationRate.Definition: Indication of the requirement of a particular natural air ventilation rate, given in air changes per hour.

TemperatureMax.name: Temperature Max
TemperatureMax.Definition: Maximal temperature of the space or zone, that is required from userdesigner view point. If no summer or winter space temperature requirements are given, it applies all year, otherwise for the intermediate period.

TemperatureMin.name: Temperature Min
TemperatureMin.Definition: Minimal temperature of the space or zone, that is required from userdesigner view point. If no summer or winter space temperature requirements are given, it applies all year, otherwise for the intermediate period.

TemperatureSetPoint.name: Temperature Set Point
TemperatureSetPoint.Definition: The temperature setpoint range and default setpoint.

TemperatureSummerMax.name: Temperature Summer Max
TemperatureSummerMax.Definition: Maximal temperature of the space or zone for the hot (summer) period, that is required from userdesigner view point and provided as requirement for cooling.

TemperatureSummerMin.name: Temperature Summer Min
TemperatureSummerMin.Definition: Minimal temperature of the space or zone for the hot (summer) period, that is required from userdesigner view point and provided as requirement for cooling.

TemperatureWinterMax.name: Temperature Winter Max
TemperatureWinterMax.Definition: Maximal temperature of the space or zone for the cold (winter) period, that is required from userdesigner view point and provided as requirement for heating.

TemperatureWinterMin.name: Temperature Winter Min
TemperatureWinterMin.Definition: Minimal temperature of the space or zone for the cold (winter) period, that is required from userdesigner view point and provided as requirement for heating.

ArtificialLighting.name: Artificial Lighting
ArtificialLighting.Definition: Indication whether this space requires artificial lighting (as natural lighting would be not sufficient). (TRUE) indicates yes (FALSE) otherwise.

Illuminance.name: Illuminance
Illuminance.Definition: Required average illuminance value for this space.

AreaPerOccupant.name: Area Per Occupant
AreaPerOccupant.Definition: Design occupancy loading for this type of usage assigned to this space.

IsOutlookDesirable.name: Is Outlook Desirable
IsOutlookDesirable.Definition: An indication of whether the outlook is desirable (set TRUE) or not (set FALSE)

MinimumHeadroom.name: Minimum Headroom
MinimumHeadroom.Definition: Headroom required for the activity assigned to this space.

OccupancyNumber.name: Occupancy Number
OccupancyNumber.Definition: Number of people required for the activity assigned to this space.

OccupancyNumberPeak.name: Occupancy Number Peak
OccupancyNumberPeak.Definition: Maximal number of people required for the activity assigned to this space in peak time.

OccupancyTimePerDay.name: Occupancy Time Per Day
OccupancyTimePerDay.Definition: The amount of time during the day that the activity is required within this space.

AirSideSystemDistributionType.name: Air Side System Distribution Type
AirSideSystemDistributionType.Definition: This enumeration defines the basic types of air side systems (e.g., Single Duct, Dual Duct, Multizone, etc.).

AirSideSystemType.name: Air Side System Type
AirSideSystemType.Definition: This enumeration specifies the basic types of possible air side systems (e.g., Constant Volume, Variable Volume, etc.).

CoolingTemperatureDelta.name: Cooling Temperature Delta
CoolingTemperatureDelta.Definition: Cooling temperature difference for calculating space air flow rates.

EnergyGainSensible.name: Energy Gain Sensible
EnergyGainSensible.Definition: The sum of total energy gains for the spaces served by the system during the peak cooling conditions, plus any system-level sensible energy gains.

EnergyGainTotal.name: Energy Gain Total
EnergyGainTotal.Definition: The total amount of energy gains for the spaces served by the system during the peak cooling conditions, plus any system-level total energy gains.

EnergyLoss.name: Energy Loss
EnergyLoss.Definition: The sum of energy losses for the spaces served by the system during the peak heating conditions.

FanPower.name: Fan Power
FanPower.Definition: Fan motor loads contributing to the cooling load.

HeatingTemperatureDelta.name: Heating Temperature Delta
HeatingTemperatureDelta.Definition: Heating temperature difference for calculating space air flow rates.

BoundaryAreaHeatLoss.name: Boundary Area Heat Loss
BoundaryAreaHeatLoss.Definition: Heat loss per unit area for the boundary object. This is a design input value for use in the absence of calculated load data.

CeilingRAPlenum.name: Ceiling Raplenum
CeilingRAPlenum.Definition: Ceiling plenum used for return air or not. TRUE Yes, FALSE No.

CoolingDesignAirFlow.name: Cooling Design Air Flow
CoolingDesignAirFlow.Definition: The air flowrate required during the peak cooling conditions.

CoolingDryBulb.name: Cooling Dry Bulb
CoolingDryBulb.Definition: Dry bulb temperature, usually for for cooling design.

CoolingRelativeHumidity.name: Cooling Relative Humidity
CoolingRelativeHumidity.Definition: Inside relative humidity for cooling design.

DesignAirFlow.name: Design Air Flow
DesignAirFlow.Definition: Design air flow rate for the space.

HeatingDesignAirFlow.name: Heating Design Air Flow
HeatingDesignAirFlow.Definition: The air flowrate required during the peak heating conditions, but could also be determined by minimum ventilation requirement or minimum air change requirements.

HeatingDryBulb.name: Heating Dry Bulb
HeatingDryBulb.Definition: Dry bulb temperature for heating design.

HeatingRelativeHumidity.name: Heating Relative Humidity
HeatingRelativeHumidity.Definition: Inside relative humidity for heating design.

SensibleHeatGain.name: Sensible Heat Gain
SensibleHeatGain.Definition: The sensible heat or energy gained by the space during the peak conditions.

TotalHeatGain.name: Total Heat Gain
TotalHeatGain.Definition: The total (sensiblelatent) amount of heat or energy gained by the space at the time of the spaces peak cooling conditions.

TotalHeatLoss.name: Total Heat Loss
TotalHeatLoss.Definition: The total amount of heat or energy lost by the space at the time of the spaces peak heating conditions.

VentilationDesignAirFlow.name: Ventilation Design Air Flow
VentilationDesignAirFlow.Definition: Ventilation outside air requirement for the space.

AirExchangeRate.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AirExchangeRate.name: Air Exchange Rate
AirExchangeRate.Definition: Loads from the air exchange rate.

DryBulbTemperature.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
DryBulbTemperature.name: Dry Bulb Temperature
DryBulbTemperature.Definition: Dry bulb temperature of the object.

EquipmentSensible.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
EquipmentSensible.name: Equipment Sensible
EquipmentSensible.Definition: Heat gains and losses from equipment.

ExhaustAir.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ExhaustAir.name: Exhaust Air

InfiltrationSensible.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
InfiltrationSensible.name: Infiltration Sensible
InfiltrationSensible.Definition: Heat gains and losses from infiltration.

Lighting.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Lighting.name: Lighting

People.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
People.name: People
People.Definition: Heat gains and losses from people.

RecirculatedAir.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RecirculatedAir.name: Recirculated Air

RelativeHumidity.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RelativeHumidity.name: Relative Humidity

TotalLatentLoad.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TotalLatentLoad.name: Total Latent Load
TotalLatentLoad.Definition: Total energy added or removed from air that affects its humidity or concentration of water vapor. If a value is less than zero (negative), then the thermal load is lost from the space. If a value is greater than zero (positive), then the thermal load is a gain to the space.

TotalRadiantLoad.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TotalRadiantLoad.name: Total Radiant Load
TotalRadiantLoad.Definition: Total electromagnetic energy added or removed by emission or absorption. If a value is less than zero (negative), then the thermal load is lost from the space. If a value is greater than zero (positive), then the thermal load is a gain to the space.

TotalSensibleLoad.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TotalSensibleLoad.name: Total Sensible Load
TotalSensibleLoad.Definition: Total energy added or removed from air that affects its temperature. If a value is less than zero (negative), then the thermal load is lost from the space. If a value is greater than zero (positive), then the thermal load is a gain to the space.

VentilationIndoorAir.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
VentilationIndoorAir.name: Ventilation Indoor Air

VentilationOutdoorAir.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
VentilationOutdoorAir.name: Ventilation Outdoor Air

AirExchangeRateTimeHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AirExchangeRateTimeHistory.name: Air Exchange Rate Time History
AirExchangeRateTimeHistory.Definition: Loads from the air exchange rate.

DryBulbTemperatureHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
DryBulbTemperatureHistory.name: Dry Bulb Temperature History
DryBulbTemperatureHistory.Definition: Loads from the dry bulb temperature.

Read the IFC documentation for more information.
EquipmentSensibleHistory.name: Equipment Sensible History
EquipmentSensibleHistory.Definition: Heat gains and losses from equipment.

ExhaustAirHistory.name: Exhaust Air History

InfiltrationSensibleHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
InfiltrationSensibleHistory.name: Infiltration Sensible History
InfiltrationSensibleHistory.Definition: Heat gains and losses from infiltration.

LightingHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
LightingHistory.name: Lighting History

PeopleHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
PeopleHistory.name: People History
PeopleHistory.Definition: Heat gains and losses from people.

RecirculatedAirHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RecirculatedAirHistory.name: Recirculated Air History

RelativeHumidityHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RelativeHumidityHistory.name: Relative Humidity History

TotalLatentLoadHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TotalLatentLoadHistory.name: Total Latent Load History
TotalLatentLoadHistory.Definition: Total energy added or removed from air that affects its humidity or concentration of water vapor. If a value is less than zero (negative), then the thermal load is lost from the space. If a value is greater than zero (positive), then the thermal load is a gain to the space.

TotalRadiantLoadHistory.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TotalRadiantLoadHistory.name: Total Radiant Load History
TotalRadiantLoadHistory.Definition: Total electromagnetic energy added or removed by emission or absorption. If a value is less than zero (negative), then the thermal load is lost from the space. If a value is greater than zero (positive), then the thermal load is a gain to the space.
