IsExternal.name: Is External
IsExternal.Definition: Indication whether the element is designed for use in the exterior (TRUE) or not (FALSE). If (TRUE) it is an external element and faces the outside of the building.

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

TactileMarking.name: Tactile Marking
TactileMarking.Definition: The kind of Tactile Marking of the element.

Thickness.name: Thickness
Thickness.Definition: The geometric thickness of the object.

Width.name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcSignal.Definition: A signal is an active device that conveys information or instructions to users, by means of an audio, visual signal or a combination of both.
IfcSignal.Name: Signal

AppliesToTrainCategory.name: Applies to Train Category
AppliesToTrainCategory.Definition: Sign information relative to train category, e.g. freight, passenger.

SignalAspectSymbol.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SignalAspectSymbol.name: Signal Aspect Symbol
SignalAspectSymbol.Definition: Content which is shown on the signal or sign, e.g. text, number, arrow or icon.

SignalAspectType.name: Signal Aspect Type
SignalAspectType.Definition: The type of aspect, e.g. 2-display aspect for distant signal, 3-display aspect for block signal.

SignLegend.name: Sign Legend
SignLegend.Definition: Text information written on the signal or sign.

ApproachSpeed.name: Approach Speed
ApproachSpeed.Definition: The design speed of trains approaching the signal if different from the line speed.

DistanceToStopMark.name: Distance to Stop Mark
DistanceToStopMark.Definition: Distance from the signal to the nearest stop mark at a platform.

HandSignallingProhibited.name: Hand Signalling Prohibited
HandSignallingProhibited.Definition: Indicates if hand signalling is prohibited in case of any failure.

HinderingObstaclesDescription.name: Hindering Obstacles Description
HinderingObstaclesDescription.Definition: Description of obstacles that hinder the visibility for the staff in the station.

LimitedClearances.name: Limited Clearances
LimitedClearances.Definition: Special conditions for placing the signal post telephone tunnels, bridges, viaducts.

NumberOfLampsNotUsed.name: Number of Lamps Not Used
NumberOfLampsNotUsed.Definition: Number of lamps which are not needed and blanked out (sealed).

RequiresBannerSignal.name: Requires Banner Signal
RequiresBannerSignal.Definition: Indicates whether a banner repeater signal is required.

RequiresOLEMesh.name: Requires Olemesh
RequiresOLEMesh.Definition: Indicates whether an OLE mesh is required to protect the signal or maintainer.

RequiresSafetyHandrail.name: Requires Safety Handrail
RequiresSafetyHandrail.Definition: Indicates whether a safety handrail is required.

SignalPostTelephoneID.name: Signal Post Telephone Id
SignalPostTelephoneID.Definition: The identifier of the signal post telephone attached to the signal.

SignalPostTelephoneType.name: Signal Post Telephone Type
SignalPostTelephoneType.Definition: Indicates the type of the signal post telephone, e.g. locked, direct line, dial phone.

SignalWalkwayLength.name: Signal Walkway Length
SignalWalkwayLength.Definition: Indicates the length of the walkway from signal to signal post telephone.

SpecialPositionArrangement.name: Special Position Arrangement
SpecialPositionArrangement.Definition: Type of special position at which the signal is placed.

SignalSightingAchievableDistance.name: Signal Sighting Achievable Distance
SignalSightingAchievableDistance.Definition: Reading distance of the signal, which is achievable with the help of mitigation works.

SignalSightingAvailableDistance.name: Signal Sighting Available Distance
SignalSightingAvailableDistance.Definition: Reading distance of the signal without having any mitigation works.

SignalSightingCombinedWithRepeater.name: Signal Sighting Combined With Repeater
SignalSightingCombinedWithRepeater.Definition: Combined reading distance for the signal and any associated repeaters.

SignalSightingMinimum.name: Signal Sighting Minimum
SignalSightingMinimum.Definition: Minimal distance in which the signal has to be readable.

SignalSightingPreferred.name: Signal Sighting Preferred
SignalSightingPreferred.Definition: Preferred distance in which the signal shall be readable.

SignalSightingRouteIndicator.name: Signal Sighting Route Indicator
SignalSightingRouteIndicator.Definition: Required reading distance for the route indicator.

SignalViewingMinimumInFront.name: Signal Viewing Minimum In Front
SignalViewingMinimumInFront.Definition: Smallest distance where the signal has to be readable (for train very close to the signal).

HasConductorRailGuardBoard.name: Has Conductor Rail Guard Board
HasConductorRailGuardBoard.Definition: Indicates if a guard board is provided.

HotStripOrientation.name: Hot Strip Orientation
HotStripOrientation.Definition: Position of the hot strip, which indicates the direction of the focus of the light beam and is given in terms like left upper quadrant (LUQ) or 5 oclock.

IsHighType.name: Is High Type
IsHighType.Definition: Indicates if the signal is high (TRUE) or dwarf (ground mounted) (FALSE).

LensDiffuserOrientation.name: Lens Diffuser Orientation
LensDiffuserOrientation.Definition: Orientation the lens diffuser has to have, which indicates the direction of the lens diffuser and is given in terms like left upper quadrant (LUQ) or 5 oclock.

LensDiffuserType.name: Lens Diffuser Type
LensDiffuserType.Definition: Type of the lens diffuser the signal is equipped with.

MaximumDisplayDistance.name: Maximum Display Distance
MaximumDisplayDistance.Definition: The maximum distance that can be displayed. The value relates only to the signal type, not to the circumstances at a special position.

NumberOfLamps.name: Number of Lamps
NumberOfLamps.Definition: Number of lamps the signal is composed of.

RailwaySignalType.name: Railway Signal Type
RailwaySignalType.Definition: The type of railway signal, e.g. home signal, starting signal, shunting signal, level crossing signal.

RequiredDisplayDistance.name: Required Display Distance
RequiredDisplayDistance.Definition: The required distance that has to be displayed. The value relates only to the signal type, not to the circumstances at a special position.

SignalHoodLength.name: Signal Hood Length
SignalHoodLength.Definition: Nominal length of the signal hood, which is the signal lamp cover against glaring sun.

SignalIndicatorType.name: Signal Indicator Type
SignalIndicatorType.Definition: Type of the indicators on a signal, e.g. route indicator, speed restriction indicator etc.

SignalMessage.name: Signal Message
SignalMessage.Definition: All possible message available at this signal, e.g. 34- display automatic blocking.

BackboardType.name: Backboard Type
BackboardType.Definition: The type of the backboard of the signal frame.

NominalWidth.name: Nominal Width
NominalWidth.Definition: The nominal overall width of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

SignalFrameBackboardDiameter.name: Signal Frame Backboard Diameter
SignalFrameBackboardDiameter.Definition: The nominal diameter of the signal frame backboard.

SignalFrameBackboardHeight.name: Signal Frame Backboard Height
SignalFrameBackboardHeight.Definition: The nominal height of the signal frame backboard.

SignalFrameType.name: Signal Frame Type
SignalFrameType.Definition: Type of frame, e.g. main frame, route indicator, speed indicator, direction indicator, etc.

SignalIndicatorType.name: Signal Indicator Type
SignalIndicatorType.Definition: Type of the indicators on a signal, e.g. route indicator, speed restriction indicator etc.

IfcSignalType.Definition: The Ifc Signal Type provides the type information for Ifc Signal occurrences.
IfcSignalType.Name: Signal Type

IfcSignType.Definition: The Ifc Sign Type provides the type information for Ifc Sign occurrences.
IfcSignType.Name: Qtovolumetric Stratum Base Quantities

IfcActionRequest.Definition: A request is the act or instance of asking for something, such as a request for information, bid submission, or performance of work.Requests may take many forms depending on the need including fault reports for maintenance, requests for small works, and purchase requests (where these are to be made through a help desk or buying function).
IfcActionRequest.Name: Action Request

RequestComments.name: Request Comments
RequestComments.Definition: Comments that may be made on the request.

RequestSourceLabel.name: Request Source Label
RequestSourceLabel.Definition: A specific name or label that further qualifies the identity of a request source. In the event of an email, this may be the email address.

RequestSourceName.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RequestSourceName.name: Request Source Name
RequestSourceName.Definition: The person making the request, where known.

LongDescription.name: Long Description
LongDescription.Definition: Detailed description of the permit. IFC4 CHANGE The attribute has been added.

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: The status currently assigned to the request. Possible values include

IfcCostItem.Definition: An Ifc Cost Item describes a cost or financial value together with descriptive information that describes its context in a form that enables it to be used within a cost schedule. An Ifc Cost Item can be used to represent the cost of goods and services, the execution of works by a process, lifecycle cost and more.Each instance of Ifc Cost Item may have a name and a description. Depending on the use for which the cost is intended, these values should be asserted on the basis of agreement. For instance, the Name attribute could be used to provide a common value that enables distinct instances to be brought together in a nesting arrangement (see below) while the Description attribute may be used to provide text used for item description in a costing schedule.An Ifc Cost Item can link one or many Ifc Cost Values representing a unit cost, total cost, or a unit cost with one or many quantities used to generate the total cost. The quantities can be given as individual quantities, or those quantities are provided as element quantities by one or many building elements. The Ifc Cost Value.Category attribute indicates the category of cost, which may be used to present the value in a particular column. For nested cost items (having Ifc Rel Nests relationship), Ifc Cost Value.Category is significant such that Ifc Cost Value.Applied Value is calculated as the sum of all nested costs having the same Ifc Cost Value.Category or if set to an asterisk (), then the sum of all nested costs of all cost types. An Ifc Cost Value may represent an original value or a value derived from formulas. For example, taxes may be calculated as a percentage of a subtotal.
IfcCostItem.Name: Cost Item

IfcCostSchedule.Definition: An Ifc Cost Schedule brings together instances of Ifc Cost Item either for the purpose of identifying purely cost information as in an estimate for constructions costs or for including cost information within another presentation form such as a work order.
IfcCostSchedule.Name: Cost Schedule

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: The current status of a cost schedule. Examples of status values that might be used for a cost schedule status include

SubmittedOn.name: Submitted On
SubmittedOn.Definition: The date and time on which the cost schedule was submitted.

UpdateDate.name: Update Date
UpdateDate.Definition: The date and time that this cost schedule is updated this allows tracking the schedule history.

IfcPermit.Definition: A permit is a permission to perform work in places and on artifacts where regulatory, security or other access restrictions apply.
IfcPermit.Name: Permit

EndDate.name: End Date
EndDate.Definition: Date and time at which the permit ceases to be valid.

EscortRequirement.name: Escort Requirement
EscortRequirement.Definition: Indicates whether or not an escort is required to accompany persons carrying out a work order at or tofrom the place of work ( TRUE) or not ( FALSE).

SpecialRequirements.name: Special Requirements
SpecialRequirements.Definition: Any additional special requirements that need to be included in the permit to work.

StartDate.name: Start Date
StartDate.Definition: Date and time from which the permit becomes valid.

LongDescription.name: Long Description
LongDescription.Definition: Detailed description of the request. IFC4 CHANGE The attribute has been added.

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: The status currently assigned to the permit. IFC4 CHANGE The attribute has been added.

IfcProjectOrder.Definition: A project order is a directive to purchase products andor perform work, such as for construction or facilities management.Project orders are typically formal contracts between two organizations, where cost and time information may be rigid or flexible according to contained schedule types and constraints.
IfcProjectOrder.Name: Project Order Work Order

LongDescription.name: Long Description
LongDescription.Definition: A detailed description of the project order describing the work to be completed.

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: The current status of a project order.Examples of status values that might be used for a project order status include

IfcRelConnectsStructuralActivity.Definition: The Ifc Rel Connects Structural Activity relationship connects a structural activity (either an action or reaction) to a structural member, structural connection, or element.
IfcRelConnectsStructuralActivity.Name: Rel Connects Structural Activity

IfcRelConnectsStructuralMember.Definition: The entity Ifc Rel Connects Structural Member defines all needed properties describing the connection between structural members and structural connection objects (nodes or supports).
IfcRelConnectsStructuralMember.Name: Rel Connects Structural Member

SupportedLength.name: Supported Length
SupportedLength.Definition: Defines the supported length of this structural connection. See Fig. for more detail.

IfcRelConnectsWithEccentricity.Definition: The entity Ifc Rel Connects With Eccentricity adds the definition of eccentricity to the connection between a structural member and a structural connection (representing either a node or support).
IfcRelConnectsWithEccentricity.Name: Rel Connects With Eccentricity

IfcStructuralAction.Definition: A structural action is a structural activity that acts upon a structural item or building element.
IfcStructuralAction.Name: Structural Action

DestabilizingLoad.name: Destabilizing Load
DestabilizingLoad.Definition: Indicates if this action may cause a stability problem. If it is FALSE, no further investigations regarding stability problems are necessary.

IfcStructuralActivity.Definition: The abstract entity Ifc Structural Activity combines the definition of actions (such as forces, displacements, etc.) and reactions (support reactions, internal forces, deflections, etc.) which are specified by using the basic load definitions from the Ifc Structural Load Resource.The differentiation between actions and reactions is realized by instantiating objects either from subclasses of Ifc Structural Action or Ifc Structural Reaction respectively. They inherit commonly needed attributes from the abstract superclass Ifc Structural Activity, notably the relationship which connects actions or reactions with connections, analysis members, or elements (subtypes of Ifc Structural Item or Ifc Element).
IfcStructuralActivity.Name: Structural Activity

GlobalOrLocal.Definition: Indicates whether the load directions refer to the global coordinate system (global to

IfcStructuralAnalysisModel.Definition: The Ifc Structural Analysis Model is used to assemble all information needed to represent a structural analysis model. It encompasses certain general properties (such as analysis type), references to all contained structural members, structural supports or connections, as well as loads and the respective load results.Important functionalities for the description of an analysis model are derived from existing IFC entitiesFrom Ifc System it inherits the ability to couple the built system via Ifc Rel Referenced In Spatial Structure to one or more Ifc Spatial Element subtypes as necessary.
IfcStructuralAnalysisModel.Name: Structural Analysis Model

IfcStructuralConnection.Definition: An Ifc Structural Connection represents a structural connection object (node connection, edge connection, or surface connection) or supports.
IfcStructuralConnection.Name: Structural Connection

IfcStructuralCurveAction.Definition: A structural curve action defines an action which is distributed over a curve. A curve action may be connected with a curve member or curve connection, or surface member or surface connection.
IfcStructuralCurveAction.Name: Structural Curve Action

ProjectedOrTrue.Definition: Defines whether load values are given per true length of the curve on which they act, or per length of the projection of the curve in load direction. The latter is only applicable to loads which act in global coordinate directions.

IfcStructuralCurveConnection.Definition: Instances of Ifc Structural Curve Connection describe edge nodes, i.e. edges where two or more surface members are joined, or edge supports. Edge curves may be straight or curved.
IfcStructuralCurveConnection.Name: Structural Curve Connection

IfcStructuralCurveMember.Definition: Instances of Ifc Structural Curve Member describe edge members, i.e. structural analysis idealizations of beams, columns, rods etc.. Curve members may be straight or curved.
IfcStructuralCurveMember.Name: Structural Curve Member

IfcStructuralCurveMemberVarying.Definition: This entity describes edge members with varying profile properties. Each instance of Ifc Structural Curve Member Varying is composed of two or more instances of Ifc Structural Curve Member with differing profile properties. These subordinate members relate to the instance of Ifc Structural Curve Member Varying by Ifc Rel Aggregates.
IfcStructuralCurveMemberVarying.Name: Structural Curve Member Varying

IfcStructuralCurveReaction.Definition: This entity defines a reaction which occurs distributed over a curve. A curve reaction may be connected with a curve member or curve connection, or surface member or surface connection.
IfcStructuralCurveReaction.Name: Structural Curve Reaction

IfcStructuralItem.Definition: The abstract entity Ifc Structural Item is the generalization of structural members and structural connections, that is, analysis idealizations of elements in the building model. It defines the relation between structural members and connections with structural activities (actions and reactions).Relationships between elements in the building model and structural items as their idealizations can be expressed by instances of Ifc Rel Assigns To Product.
IfcStructuralItem.Name: Structural Item

IfcStructuralLinearAction.Definition: This entity defines an action with constant value which is distributed over a curve.
IfcStructuralLinearAction.Name: Structural Linear Action

IfcStructuralLoadCase.Definition: A load case is a load group, commonly used to group loads from the same action source.
IfcStructuralLoadCase.Name: Structural Load Case

SelfWeightCoefficients.name: Self Weight Coefficients
SelfWeightCoefficients.Definition: The self weight coefficients specify ratios at which loads due to weight of members shall be included in the load case. These loads are not explicitly modeled as instances of Ifc Structural Action. Instead they shall be calculated according to geometry, section, and material of each member.The three components of the self weight vector correspond with the x,y,z directions of the so-called global coordinates, i.e. the directions of the shared Object Placement of all items in an Ifc Structural Analysis Model. For example, if the object placement defines a z axis which is upright like the Ifc Projects world coordinate system, then the self weight coefficients would typically be 0.,0.,-1. in a load case of dead loads with self weight.The overall coefficient in the inherited attribute Coefficient shall not be applied to Self Weight Coefficients of the same instance of Ifc Structural Load Case. It only applies to actions and load groups which are grouped below the load case, not to the load cases computed self weight.

IfcStructuralLoadGroup.Definition: The entity Ifc Structural Load Group is used to structure the physical impacts. By using the grouping features inherited from Ifc Group, instances of Ifc Structural Action (or its subclasses) and of Ifc Structural Load Group can be used to define load groups, load cases and load combinations. (See also Ifc Load Group Type Enum.)
IfcStructuralLoadGroup.Name: Structural Load Group

ActionSource.Definition: Source of actions in the group. Normally needed if Predefined Type specifies a LOADCASE.

ActionType.Definition: Type of actions in the group. Normally needed if Predefined Type specifies a LOADCASE.

Coefficient.name: Coefficient
Coefficient.Definition: Load factor. If omitted, a factor is not yet known or not specified. A load factor of 1.0 shall be explicitly exported as Coefficient 1.0.

Purpose.name: Purpose
Purpose.Definition: Description of the purpose of this instance. Among else, possible values of the Purpose of load combinations are SLS, ULS, ALS to indicate serviceability, ultimate, or accidental limit state.

IfcStructuralMember.Definition: The abstract entity Ifc Structural Member is the superclass of all structural items which represent the idealized structural behavior of building elements.
IfcStructuralMember.Name: Structural Member

IfcStructuralPlanarAction.Definition: This entity defines an action with constant value which is distributed over a surface.
IfcStructuralPlanarAction.Name: Structural Planar Action

IfcStructuralPointAction.Definition: This entity defines an action which acts on a point. A point action is typically connected with a point connection. It may also be connected with a curve member or curve connection, or surface member or surface connection.
IfcStructuralPointAction.Name: Structural Point Action

IfcStructuralPointConnection.Definition: Instances of Ifc Structural Point Connection describe structural nodes or point supports.
IfcStructuralPointConnection.Name: Structural Point Connection

IfcStructuralPointReaction.Definition: This entity defines a reaction which occurs at a point. A point reaction is typically connected with a point connection. It may also be connected with a curve member or curve connection, or surface member or surface connection.
IfcStructuralPointReaction.Name: Structural Point Reaction

IfcStructuralReaction.Definition: A structural reaction is a structural activity that results from a structural action imposed to a structural item or building element. Examples are support reactions, internal forces, and deflections.
IfcStructuralReaction.Name: Structural Reaction

IfcStructuralResultGroup.Definition: Instances of the entity Ifc Structural Result Group are used to group results of structural analysis calculations and to capture the connection to the underlying basic load group. The basic functionality for grouping inherited from Ifc Group is used to collect instances from Ifc Structural Reaction or its respective subclasses.
IfcStructuralResultGroup.Name: Structural Result Group

IsLinear.name: Is Linear
IsLinear.Definition: This value allows to easily recognize whether a linear analysis has been applied (allowing the superposition of analysis results).

TheoryType.Definition: Specifies the analysis theory used to obtain the respective results.

IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.Definition: This entity defines an action which is distributed over a surface. A surface action may be connected with a surface member or surface connection.
IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.Name: Structural Surface Action

ProjectedOrTrue.Definition: Defines whether load values are given per true lengths of the surface on which they act, or per lengths of the projection of the surface in load direction. The latter is only applicable to loads which act in global coordinate directions.

IfcStructuralSurfaceConnection.Definition: Instances of Ifc Structural Surface Connection describe face nodes, i.e. faces where two or more surface members are joined, or face supports. Face surfaces may be planar or curved.
IfcStructuralSurfaceConnection.Name: Structural Surface Connection

IfcStructuralSurfaceMember.Definition: Instances of Ifc Structural Surface Member describe face members, that is, structural analysis idealizations of slabs, walls, and shells. Surface members may be planar or curved.
IfcStructuralSurfaceMember.Name: Structural Surface Member

Thickness.name: Thickness
Thickness.Definition: Defines the typically understood thickness of the structural surface member, measured normal to its reference surface.

IfcStructuralSurfaceMemberVarying.Definition: This entity describes surface members with varying section properties. The properties are provided by means of PsetStructural Surface Member Varying Thickness via Ifc Rel Defines By Properties, or by means of aggregation An instance of Ifc Structural Surface Member Varying may be composed of two or more instances of Ifc Structural Surface Member with differing section properties. These subordinate members relate to the instance of Ifc Structural Surface Member Varying by Ifc Rel Aggregates.
IfcStructuralSurfaceMemberVarying.Name: Structural Surface Member Varying

Location1Global.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Location1Global.name: Location1Global
Location1Global.Definition: Global X,Y,Z coordinates of the point in which Thickness1 is given

Location1Local.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Location1Local.name: Location1Local
Location1Local.Definition: Local x,y coordinates of the point in which Thickness1 is given

Location2Global.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Location2Global.name: Location2Global
Location2Global.Definition: Global X,Y,Z coordinates of the point in which Thickness2 is given

Location2Local.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Location2Local.name: Location2Local
Location2Local.Definition: Local x,y coordinates of the point in which Thickness2 is given

Location3Global.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Location3Global.name: Location3Global
Location3Global.Definition: Global X,Y,Z coordinates of the point in which Thickness3 is given

Location3Local.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Location3Local.name: Location3Local
Location3Local.Definition: Local x,y coordinates of the point in which Thickness3 is given

Thickness1.name: Thickness1
Thickness1.Definition: First thickness parameter of a surface member with varying thickness

Thickness2.name: Thickness2
Thickness2.Definition: Second thickness parameter of a surface member with varying thickness

Thickness3.name: Thickness3
Thickness3.Definition: Third thickness parameter of a surface member with varying thickness

IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.Definition: This entity defines a reaction which occurs distributed over a surface. A surface reaction may be connected with a surface member or surface connection.
IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.Name: Structural Surface Member Varying Thickness

IfcCaissonFoundation.Definition: Caisson Foundation essentially is a hollow box that can be either open or closed.(
IfcCaissonFoundation.Name: Caisson Foundation

IfcCaissonFoundationType.Definition: Enumeration defining the Caisson Foundation Types.
IfcCaissonFoundationType.Name: Caisson Foundation Type

IfcDeepFoundation.Definition: Deep foundation is a type of foundation that transfers loads deeper than shallow foundation below the soft soils not capable of bearing the above structure. Depending on the soil strength it might have to reach down to the rock layer.Deep foundation is a new supertype incorporating the existing Ifc Pile and the new Ifc Caisson Foundation.
IfcDeepFoundation.Name: Deep Foundation

IfcFooting.Definition: A footing is a part of the foundation of a structure that spreads and transmits the load to the soil. A footing is also characterized as shallow foundation, where the loads are transferred to the ground near the surface.
IfcFooting.Name: Footing

AssemblyPlace.name: Assembly Place
AssemblyPlace.Definition: Enumeration defining where the assembly is intended to take place, either in a factory, other offsite location or on the building site.

CastingMethod.name: Casting Method
CastingMethod.Definition: The method of casting the concrete into its designed form.

ConcreteCover.name: Concrete Cover
ConcreteCover.Definition: The protective concrete cover at the reinforcing bars according to local building regulations.

ConcreteCoverAtLinks.name: Concrete Cover At Links
ConcreteCoverAtLinks.Definition: The protective concrete cover at the reinforcement links according to local building regulations.

ConcreteCoverAtMainBars.name: Concrete Cover At Main Bars
ConcreteCoverAtMainBars.Definition: The protective concrete cover at the main reinforcing bars according to local building regulations.

ConstructionToleranceClass.name: Construction Tolerance Class
ConstructionToleranceClass.Definition: Classification designation of the on-site construction tolerances according to local standards.

DimensionalAccuracyClass.name: Dimensional Accuracy Class
DimensionalAccuracyClass.Definition: Classification designation of the dimensional accuracy requirement according to local standards.

ExposureClass.name: Exposure Class
ExposureClass.Definition: Classification of exposure to environmental conditions, usually specified in accordance with the concrete design code which is applied in the project.

ReinforcementAreaRatio.name: Reinforcement Area Ratio
ReinforcementAreaRatio.Definition: The required ratio of the effective area of the reinforcement to the effective area of the concrete At any section of a reinforced concrete structural element.

ReinforcementStrengthClass.name: Reinforcement Strength Class
ReinforcementStrengthClass.Definition: Classification of the reinforcement strength in accordance with the concrete design code which is applied in the project. The reinforcing strength class often combines strength and ductility.

ReinforcementVolumeRatio.name: Reinforcement Volume Ratio
ReinforcementVolumeRatio.Definition: The required ratio of the effective mass of the reinforcement to the effective volume of the concrete of a reinforced concrete structural element.

StrengthClass.name: Strength Class
StrengthClass.Definition: Classification of the concrete strength in accordance with the concrete design code which is applied in the project.

StructuralClass.name: Structural Class
StructuralClass.Definition: The structural class defined for the concrete structure (e.g. 1).

LoadBearing.name: Load Bearing
LoadBearing.Definition: Indicates whether the object is intended to carry loads (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

Status.name: Status
Status.Definition: Status of the element, predominately used in renovation or retrofitting projects. The status can be assigned to as New - element designed as new addition, Existing - element exists and remains, Demolish - element existed but is to be demolished, Temporary - element will exists only temporary (like a temporary support structure).

AsBuiltLocationNumber.name: As Built Location Number
AsBuiltLocationNumber.Definition: Defines a unique location within a structure, the slot into which the piece was installed. Where pieces share the same piece mark, they can be interchanged. The value is only known after erection.

PieceMark.name: Piece Mark
PieceMark.Definition: Defines a unique piece for production purposes. All pieces with the same piece mark value are identical and interchangeable. The piece mark may be composed of sub-parts that have specific locally defined meaning (e.g. B-1A may denote a beam, of generic type 1 and specific shape A).

SerialNumber.name: Serial Number
SerialNumber.Definition: The manufacturers serial number assigned to an occurrence of a product.

TypeDesignation.name: Type Designation
TypeDesignation.Definition: Type designator for the element. The content depends on local standards. Eg. Bull nose, Half batter, Dropper, Chamfer etc

BatterAtEnd.name: Batter At End
BatterAtEnd.Definition: The angle, in radians, by which the formwork at the ending face of a piece is to be rotated from the vertical in order to compensate for the rotation of the face that will occur once the piece is stripped from its form, inducing camber due to eccentric prestressing.

BatterAtStart.name: Batter At Start
BatterAtStart.Definition: The angle, in radians, by which the formwork at the starting face of a piece is to be rotated from the vertical in order to compensate for the rotation of the face that will occur once the piece is stripped from its form, inducing camber due to eccentric prestressing.

CamberAtMidspan.name: Camber At Midspan
CamberAtMidspan.Definition: The camber deflection, measured from the midpoint of a cambered face of a piece to the midpoint of the chord joining the ends of the same face, as shown in the figure below, divided by the original (nominal) straight length of the face of the piece.

CornerChamfer.name: Corner Chamfer
CornerChamfer.Definition: The chamfer in the corners of the precast element. The chamfer is presumed to be equal in both directions.

DesignLocationNumber.name: Design Location Number
DesignLocationNumber.Definition: Defines a unique location within a structure, the slot for which the piece was designed.

FormStrippingStrength.name: Form Stripping Strength
FormStrippingStrength.Definition: The minimum required compressive strength of the concrete at form stripping time.

HollowCorePlugging.name: Hollow Core Plugging
HollowCorePlugging.Definition: A descriptive label for how the hollow core ends are treated they may be left open, closed with a plug, or sealed with cast concrete. Values would be, for example Unplugged, Plugged, Sealed With Concrete. This property applies to hollow core slabs only.

InitialTension.name: Initial Tension
InitialTension.Definition: The initial stress of the tendon. This property applies to prestressed concrete elements only.

LiftingStrength.name: Lifting Strength
LiftingStrength.Definition: The minimum required compressive strength of the concrete when the concrete element is lifted.

ManufacturingToleranceClass.name: Manufacturing Tolerance Class
ManufacturingToleranceClass.Definition: Classification designation of the manufacturing tolerances according to local standards.

PieceMark.name: Piece Mark
PieceMark.Definition: Defines a unique piece for production purposes. All pieces with the same piece mark value are identical and interchangeable. The piece mark may be composed of sub-parts that have specific locally defined meaning (e.g. B-1A may denote a beam, of generic type 1 and specific shape A).

ReleaseStrength.name: Release Strength
ReleaseStrength.Definition: The minimum required compressive strength of the concrete when the tendon stress is released. This property applies to prestressed concrete elements only.

Shortening.name: Shortening
Shortening.Definition: The ratio of the distance by which a precast piece is shortened after release from its form (due to compression induced by prestressing) to its original (nominal) length.

SupportDuringTransportDescription.name: Support During Transport Description
SupportDuringTransportDescription.Definition: Textual description of how the concrete element is supported during transportation.

SupportDuringTransportDocReference.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SupportDuringTransportDocReference.name: Support During Transport Doc Reference
SupportDuringTransportDocReference.Definition: Reference to an external document defining how the concrete element is supported during transportation.

TendonRelaxation.name: Tendon Relaxation
TendonRelaxation.Definition: The maximum allowable relaxation of the tendon (usually expressed as 1000 h).This property applies to prestressed concrete elements only.

TransportationStrength.name: Transportation Strength
TransportationStrength.Definition: The minimum required compressive strength of the concrete required for transportation.

Twisting.name: Twisting
Twisting.Definition: The angle, in radians, through which the end face of a precast piece is rotated with respect to its starting face, along its longitudinal axis, as a result of non-aligned supports. This measure is also termed the warping angle.

TypeDesignation.name: Type Designation
TypeDesignation.Definition: Type designator for the element. The content depends on local standards. Eg. Bull nose, Half batter, Dropper, Chamfer etc

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

XDirectionLowerBarCount.name: Xdirection Lower Bar Count
XDirectionLowerBarCount.Definition: The number of bars with X direction lower bar.

XDirectionUpperBarCount.name: Xdirection Upper Bar Count
XDirectionUpperBarCount.Definition: The number of bars with X direction upper bar.

YDirectionLowerBarCount.name: Ydirection Lower Bar Count
YDirectionLowerBarCount.Definition: The number of bars with Y direction lower bar.

YDirectionUpperBarCount.name: Ydirection Upper Bar Count
YDirectionUpperBarCount.Definition: The number of bars with Y direction upper bar.

CrossingLowerBarPitch.name: Crossing Lower Bar Pitch
CrossingLowerBarPitch.Definition: The pitch length of the crossing lower bar.

CrossingUpperBarPitch.name: Crossing Upper Bar Pitch
CrossingUpperBarPitch.Definition: The pitch length of the crossing upper bar.

Reference.name: Reference
Reference.Definition: Reference ID for this specified type in this project (e.g. type A-1), Also referred to as construction type. It should be provided as an alternative to the name of the object type, if the software does not support object types and no classification reference to a recognized classification system used.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION The Reference property is deprecated and shall no longer be used, use attribute Name on the relating type instead.

CrossSectionArea.name: Cross Section Area
CrossSectionArea.Definition: Total area of the cross section (or profile) of the object.

GrossSurfaceArea.name: Gross Surface Area
GrossSurfaceArea.Definition: Total gross area of the object, normally generated as perimeter length 2 cross section area. It is the sum of Outer Surface Area (2 x Cross Section Area) and shall only be given, if the Outer Surface Area and Cross Section Area cannot be established separately.

GrossVolume.name: Gross Volume
GrossVolume.Definition: Total gross volume of the object. Openings, recesses, enclosed objects and projections are not taken into account.

GrossWeight.name: Gross Weight
GrossWeight.Definition: Total Gross Weight of the object without any add-on parts and not taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

NetVolume.name: Net Volume
NetVolume.Definition: Total net volume of the object, taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

NetWeight.name: Net Weight
NetWeight.Definition: Total net weight of the object without add-on parts, taking into account possible processing features (cut-outs, etc.) or openings and recesses.

OuterSurfaceArea.name: Outer Surface Area
OuterSurfaceArea.Definition: Total area of the surfaces of the object (not taking into account the end cap areas), normally generated as perimeter length in case of extrusions.

Width.name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcFootingType.Definition: The building element type Ifc Footing Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of footings. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcFootingType.Name: Footing Type

IfcPile.Definition: A pile is a slender timber, concrete, or steel structural element, driven, jetted, or otherwise embedded on end in the ground for the purpose of supporting a load. A pile is also characterized as deep foundation, where the loads are transferred to deeper subsurface layers.
IfcPile.Name: Pile

ConstructionType.Definition: Deprecated. IFC4 CHANGE Material profile association capability by means of Ifc Rel Associates Material has been added. The attribute Construction Type should not be used whenever its information can be provided by a material profile set, either associated with the Ifc Pile object or, if present, with a corresponding instance of Ifc Pile Type.

IfcPileType.Definition: The building element type Ifc Pile Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of piles. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcPileType.Name: Pile Type

IfcReinforcementDefinitionProperties.Definition: Ifc Reinforcement Definition Properties defines the cross section properties of reinforcement included in reinforced concrete building elements. The property set definition may be used both in conjunction with insitu and precast structures.This subtype of Ifc Property Set Definition is used to define the reinforcement properties in early design stages, such as in requirement definition or scheme design. In later design stages explicit instances of subtypes of Ifc Reinforcing Element are used. The intended usage may be indicated using the Definition Type attribute value as a designator recommended values are Reinforcement area requirement or Reinforcement configuration requirement. Other values may be used according to local standards.Only one property set definition of this kind is used for each concrete building element in each intended usage indicated by the Definition Type attribute value. This set then defines a list of cross section properties in a discrete number of longitudinal sections as instances of Ifc Section Reinforcement Properties (one for each structural reinforcement bar role), which in turn have a section cross section property defined as a profile and a number of reinforcement properties, one for each steel grade bar type.
IfcReinforcementDefinitionProperties.Name: Reinforcement Definition Properties

DefinitionType.name: Definition Type
DefinitionType.Definition: Descriptive type name applied to reinforcement definition properties.

IfcReinforcingBar.Definition: A reinforcing bar is usually made of steel with manufactured deformations in the surface, and used in concrete and masonry construction to provide additional strength. A single instance of this class may represent one or many of actual rebars, for example a row of rebars.
IfcReinforcingBar.Name: Reinforcing Bar

BarLength.name: Bar Length
BarLength.Definition: The total length of the reinforcing bar. The total length of bended bars are calculated according to local standards with corrections for the bends.

BarSurface.Definition: Indicator for whether the bar surface is plain or textured.

CrossSectionArea.name: Cross Section Area
CrossSectionArea.Definition: The effective cross-section area of the reinforcing bar.

NominalDiameter.name: Nominal Diameter
NominalDiameter.Definition: The nominal diameter defining the cross-section size of the reinforcing bar.

BendingShapeCode.name: Bending Shape Code
BendingShapeCode.Definition: Shape code per a standard like ACI 315, ISO 3766, or a similar standard. It is presumed that a single standard for defining the bar bending is used throughout the project and that this standard is referenced from the Ifc Project object through the Ifc Document Reference mechanism.

IfcReinforcingBarType.Definition: The reinforcing element type Ifc Reinforcing Bar Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of reinforcing bars. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcReinforcingBarType.Name: Reinforcing Bar Type

IfcReinforcingElement.Definition: A reinforcing element represents bars, wires, strands, meshes, tendons, and other components embedded in concrete in such a manner that the reinforcement and the concrete act together in resisting forces.
IfcReinforcingElement.Name: Reinforcing Element

SteelGrade.name: Steel Grade
SteelGrade.Definition: Deprecated. IFC4 CHANGE Attribute deprecated. Use material association at Ifc Reinforcing Element Type instead.

IfcReinforcingElementType.Definition: The element component type Ifc Reinforcing Element Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of reinforcing elements. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcReinforcingElementType.Name: Reinforcing Element Type

IfcReinforcingMesh.Definition: A reinforcing mesh is a series of longitudinal and transverse wires or bars of various gauges, arranged at right angles to each other and welded at all points of intersection usually used for concrete slab reinforcement. It is also known as welded wire fabric. In scope are plane meshes as well as bent meshes.
IfcReinforcingMesh.Name: Reinforcing Mesh

LongitudinalBarCrossSectionArea.name: Longitudinal Bar Cross Section Area
LongitudinalBarCrossSectionArea.Definition: The effective cross-section area of the longitudinal bars of the mesh.

LongitudinalBarNominalDiameter.name: Longitudinal Bar Nominal Diameter
LongitudinalBarNominalDiameter.Definition: The nominal diameter denoting the cross-section size of the longitudinal bars.

LongitudinalBarSpacing.name: Longitudinal Bar Spacing
LongitudinalBarSpacing.Definition: The spacing between the longitudinal bars. Note an even distribution of bars is presumed other cases are handled by classification or property sets.

MeshLength.name: Mesh Length
MeshLength.Definition: The overall length of the mesh measured in its longitudinal direction.

MeshWidth.name: Mesh Width
MeshWidth.Definition: The overall width of the mesh measured in its transversal direction.

TransverseBarCrossSectionArea.name: Transverse Bar Cross Section Area
TransverseBarCrossSectionArea.Definition: The effective cross-section area of the transverse bars of the mesh.

TransverseBarNominalDiameter.name: Transverse Bar Nominal Diameter
TransverseBarNominalDiameter.Definition: The nominal diameter denoting the cross-section size of the transverse bars.

TransverseBarSpacing.name: Transverse Bar Spacing
TransverseBarSpacing.Definition: The spacing between the transverse bars. Note an even distribution of bars is presumed other cases are handled by classification or property sets.

BendingShapeCode.name: Bending Shape Code
BendingShapeCode.Definition: If this mesh type is bent rather than planar, this attribute provides a shape code per a standard like ACI 315, ISO 3766, or a similar standard. It is presumed that a single standard for defining the mesh bending is used throughout the project and that this standard is referenced from the Ifc Project object through the Ifc Document Reference mechanism.

IfcReinforcingMeshType.Definition: The reinforcing element type Ifc Reinforcing Mesh Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of reinforcing meshs. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcReinforcingMeshType.Name: Reinforcing Mesh Type

IfcSurfaceFeature.Definition: A surface feature is a modification at (onto, or into) of the surface of an element. Parts of the surface of the entire surface may be affected. The volume and mass of the element may be increased, remain unchanged, or be decreased by the surface feature, depending on manufacturing technology. However, any increase or decrease of volume is small compared to the total volume of the element.The partwhole relationship is established by an aggregation relationship object, expressing the decomposition of an element type into one or more additive elements (element parts) and zero or more feature elements.
IfcSurfaceFeature.Name: Surface Feature

IfcTendon.Definition: A tendon is a steel element such as a wire, cable, bar, rod, or strand used to impart prestress to concrete when the element is tensioned.
IfcTendon.Name: Tendon

AnchorageSlip.name: Anchorage Slip
AnchorageSlip.Definition: The deformation of an anchor or slippage of tendons when the prestressing device is released.

CrossSectionArea.name: Cross Section Area
CrossSectionArea.Definition: The effective cross-section area of the prestressed part of the tendon.

FrictionCoefficient.name: Friction Coefficient
FrictionCoefficient.Definition: The friction coefficient between tendon and tendon sheet while the tendon is unbonded.

MinCurvatureRadius.name: Min Curvature Radius
MinCurvatureRadius.Definition: The smallest curvature radius calculated on the whole effective length of the tendon where the tension properties are still valid.

NominalDiameter.name: Nominal Diameter
NominalDiameter.Definition: The nominal diameter defining the cross-section size of the prestressed part of the tendon.

PreStress.name: Pre Stress
PreStress.Definition: The prestress to be applied on the tendon.

TensionForce.name: Tension Force
TensionForce.Definition: The maximum allowed tension force that can be applied on the tendon.

SheathDiameter.name: Sheath Diameter
SheathDiameter.Definition: Diameter of the sheeth (duct) around the tendon, if there is one with this type of tendon.

IfcTendonAnchor.Definition: A tendon anchor is the end connection for tendons in prestressed or posttensioned concrete.
IfcTendonAnchor.Name: Tendon Anchor

IfcTendonAnchorType.Definition: The reinforcing element type Ifc Tendon Anchor Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of tendon anchors. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcTendonAnchorType.Name: Tendon Anchor Type

IfcTendonConduit.Definition: A Tendon Conduit represents the components of the conduit system for tendons embedded in concrete structure.
IfcTendonConduit.Name: Tendon Conduit

IfcTendonType.Definition: The reinforcing element type Ifc Tendon Type defines commonly shared information for occurrences of tendons. The set of shared information may includecommon properties with shared property sets
IfcTendonType.Name: Tendon Type

IfcVoidingFeature.Definition: A voiding feature is a modification of an element which reduces its volume. Such a feature may be manufactured in different ways, for example by cutting, drilling, or milling of members made of various materials, or by inlays into the formwork of cast members made of materials such as concrete.The standard use of instances of Ifc Voiding Feature is as a part of element type objects (instances of subtypes of Ifc Element Type). The partwhole relationship is established by an aggregation relationship object, expressing the decomposition of an element type into one or more additive elements (element parts) and zero or more feature elements.
IfcVoidingFeature.Name: Qtoreinforcing Element Base Quantities

BendRadius.Definition: The radius of bending if circular arc or zero if sharp bend.

IfcCableCarrierFitting.CONNECTOR.Name: Connector

IfcCableCarrierFitting.CROSS.Name: Cross

IfcCableCarrierFitting.JUNCTION.Definition: A fitting with typically more than two ports used to redistribute flow among the ports andor to change the direction of flow between connected elements (e.g, tee, cross, wye, etc.).IFC4.3.0.0 CHANGE New enumeration
IfcCableCarrierFitting.JUNCTION.Name: Junction

JunctionRightAngle.Definition: The change of direction of flow for the right junction where 0 indicates straight segment.

JunctionRightRadius.name: Junction Right Radius
JunctionRightRadius.Definition: The radius of bending for the right junction where 0 indicates sharp bend.

JunctionType.name: Junction Type
JunctionType.Definition: The type of junction. TEE3 ports, CROSS 4 ports.

IfcCableCarrierFitting.REDUCER.Definition: A fitting that changes the physical size of the main route of the cable carrier.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION Use TRANSITION instead.
IfcCableCarrierFitting.REDUCER.Name: Reducer

IfcCableCarrierFitting.TEE.Definition: A fitting at which a branch is taken from the main route of the cable carrier.IFC4.3.0.0 DEPRECATION Use JUNCTION instead.
IfcCableCarrierFitting.TEE.Name: Tee

IfcCableCarrierFitting.TRANSITION.Definition: A fitting with typically two ports having different shapes or sizes. Can also be used to change the direction of flow between connected elements.IFC4.3.0.0 CHANGE New enumeration
IfcCableCarrierFitting.TRANSITION.Name: Transition
